s franchise has expanded beyond apps and animated series. The franchise also sells branded merchandise and music videos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://social.techcrunch.com/2011/12/14/outfit7s-talking-friends-merchandise-aims-to-invade-your-closet/|title=Outfit7\u2019s Talking Friends Merchandise Aims To Invade Your Closet|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref>\n\nTalking Tom and Talking Angela's music video for their single \"You Get Me\", created in cooperation with [[Walt Disney Records]]/[[Hollywood Records]], has received over 350 million views on [[YouTube]] as of March 2020.<ref name=\"auto\"/> Talking Angela has also recorded her first solo song called \u2018That's Falling in Love\u2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tom and Angela - That's Falling in Love (Video Teaser)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s04noJJ5xkg|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=6 December 2012}}</ref> Talking Tom and Talking Angela\u2019s \"Stand By Me\" received 26 million views as on April 2020.<ref>{{Citation|title=Tom and Angela - Stand By Me (NEW Music video from Talking Tom and Friends)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xUFio_-VzmQ|language=en|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref>\n\nTalking Tom and Friends launched a range of interactive toys called Superstar in 2012. The plush toys talk and interact with multiple Talking Tom and Friends apps, as well as with each other, using a voice recognition system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pocket-lint.com/parenting/reviews/118486-talking-tom-superstar-plush-toy-review|title=Talking Tom Superstar pictures and hands-on|last=Pocket-lint|date=2012-12-17|website=Pocket-lint|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref> The series has since been discontinued.\n\n==Controversies==\n===Paedophile Hoax===\nIn February 2014, ''Talking Angela'' was the subject of an Internet hoax claiming that it encourages children to disclose personal information about themselves, which is ostensibly then used by [[pedophile|paedophile]]s to identify the location of these children. The rumor, which was widely circulated on [[Facebook]] and various websites claiming to be dedicated to parenting, claims that Angela, the game's main character, asks the game's user for private personal information using the game's text-chat feature. Other versions of the rumor even attribute the disappearance of a child to the app,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.theepochtimes.com/n3/582669-talking-angela-game-some-people-still-believe-hoax-that-human-is-watching-them/ | title=Talking Angela Game: Some People Still Believe Hoax That Human is Watching Them | work=[[The Epoch Times]] | date=25 March 2014 | accessdate=11 May 2014 | author=Stieber, Zachary}}</ref> or claim that it is run by a pedophile ring, while some go so far as to even claim that the user is recorded by the camera and can be seen in Angela\u2019s eyes.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.myfoxdc.com/story/24776902/talking-angela-app-at-center-of-hoax#axzz31SUpeeJU | title=Talking Angela app at center of hoax | work=[[My Fox DC]] | date=20 February 2014 | accessdate=11 May 2014 | author=Azar, Kellee | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512183057/http://www.myfoxdc.com/story/24776902/talking-angela-app-at-center-of-hoax#axzz31SUpeeJU | archivedate=12 May 2014 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The former rumor originated from an article on [[Huzlers]], which has since been proven to be fake, like many articles on the satirical website.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.theepochtimes.com/n3/523560-talking-angela-app-game-hoax-7-year-old-eli-moreno-missing-after-installing-app-article-is-fake/ | title=Talking Angela App Game Hoax: \u20187 Year Old Eli Moreno Missing After Installing App\u2019 Article Isn\u2019t Real | work=The Epoch Times | date=22 February 2014 | accessdate=13 May 2014 | author=Phillips, Jack}}</ref> The rumour has been claimed to be true even by YouTubers and even on the app\u2019s review page on the [[App Store (iOS)|Apple App Store]] and the [[Google Play Store]],even though there have been no verified reports of the said events happening.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apps.apple.com/us/app/talking-angela/id554936514|title=\u200eTalking Angela|website=App Store|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.outfit7.talkingangelafree&hl=en_IN|title=Talking Angela \u2013 Apps on Google Play|website=play.google.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nIt was debunked by [[Snopes.com]] soon afterwards. The site's owners, Barbara and David Mikkelson, reported that they had tried to \"prompt\" it to give responses asking for private information but were unsuccessful, even when asking it explicitly sexual questions.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.snopes.com/computer/internet/angela.asp | title=Talking Angela | work=[[Snopes]] | date=19 February 2014 | accessdate=10 May 2014 | author=Mikkelson, Barbara}}</ref> While it is true that in the game with child mode off Angela does ask for the user's name, age and personal preferences to determine conversation topics, Outfit7 has said that this information is all \"anonymized\" and all personal information is removed from it. It is also impossible for a person to take control of what Angela says in the game, since the app is based on chat bot software.<ref name=\"today\">{{cite web | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2014/02/20/talking-angela-app-scare-hoax/5635337/ | title=Talking Angela app scare based on a hoax | work=[[USA Today]] | date=20 February 2014 | accessdate=10 May 2014 | author=Lee, Jolie}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the hoax was revived again on Facebook, prompting online security company [[Sophos]] and [[The Guardian]] to debunk it again.<ref name=\":0\" /> Sophos employee Paul Ducklin wrote on the company's blog that the message being posted on Facebook promoting the hoax was \"close to 600 rambling, repetitious words, despite claiming at the start that it didn\u2019t have words to describe the situation. It's ill-written, and borders on being illiterate and incomprehensible.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/feb/17/talking-angela-app-children-facebook-chain-letter | title=No, the Talking Angela app is not dangerous for your children | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=17 February 2014 | accessdate=10 May 2014 | author=Dredge, Stuart}}</ref> [[Bruce Wilcox]], one of the game's programmers, has attributed the hoax's popularity to the fact that the chatbot program in ''Talking Angela'' is so realistic.<ref name=cnet/> \n\nHowever, genuine concern has been raised that the game's child mode may be too easy for children to turn off, which, if they did, would allow them to purchase \"coins\", which can be used as currency in the game, via iTunes.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/why-talking-angela-app-completely-safe-your-children-1437287 | title=Why the Talking Angela App is Completely Safe For Your Children | work=[[International Business Times]] | date=20 February 2014 | accessdate=10 May 2014 | author=Russon, Mary-Ann}}</ref> Disabling child mode also enables the chat feature, which, while not \"connecting your children to pedophiles,\" still raises concerns as well, according to Stuart Dredge, a journalist from [[The Guardian]]. Dredge wrote that in chat mode, Angela asks for information such as the user's name.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/feb/18/talking-angela-app-children-safety | title=What the Talking Angela app is really saying to your kids | work=The Guardian | date=20 February 2014 | accessdate=12 May 2014 | author=Dredge, Stuart}}</ref>\n\n====Impact====\nThe scare has significantly boosted the game's popularity, and is credited with helping the app make it into the top 10 free iPhone apps soon after the hoax became widely known in February 2015<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.gottabemobile.com/2014/02/19/talking-angela-app/ | title=Talking Angela App Scare Skyrockets App to Top of Charts | work=Gottabemobile | date=19 February 2014 | accessdate=10 May 2014 | author=Smith, Josh}}</ref> and 3rd most popular for all iPhone apps at the start of the following month.<ref name=\"cnet\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cnet.com/news/talking-angela-programmer-talks-hoaxes-ai-mastery-q-a/ | title='Talking Angela' programmer talks hoaxes, AI mastery (Q&A) | work=[[CNET]] | date=1 March 2014 | accessdate=10 May 2014 | author=Terdiman, Daniel}}</ref>\n\n=== Age Inappropriate Advertising ===\nIn 2015, the ''My Talking Tom'' app was reported for having advertised age-inappropriate advertisements for adult services. The [[Advertising Standards Authority (United Kingdom)|Advertising Standards Authority]] of the [[United Kingdom]] ruled that [[Online advertising|advertising]] for an [[adult web site]] was delivered to [[underage children]] via the app.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibtimes.co.uk/my-talking-tom-iphone-android-kitten-app-children-asked-users-if-they-wanna-fk-1532487|title=My Talking Tom: Ads asked children if they \\'wanna f**k\\' in Android and iPhone app|date=2015-12-09|website=International Business Times UK|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/my-talking-tom-game-explicit-sex-ads-irresponsibly-placed-in-smartphone-app-for-children-a6766476.html|title=Explicit sex ads appeared in a smartphone app for children|date=2015-12-09|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> The ASA noted that Outfit7 \"had a strict advertising policy\" but that the company \"had not been able to identify which [[ad network]] had served an age-inappropriate ad on a children\u2019s app\" and how the advertisements were shown in the app.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asa.org.uk/rulings/mobjizz-ltd-a15-296967.html|title=Mobjizz Ltd|last=Practice|first=Advertising Standards Authority {{!}} Committee of Advertising|website=www.asa.org.uk|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n''My Talking Tom'' had over 11 million downloads and was the top games app in 135 countries worldwide within 10 days of its launch.<ref>{{cite web|title=And in first place is\u2026 \u2018My Talking Tom\u2019 App Hits The Top Spot|url=http://www.ltwmag.com/news/latest_news/and_in_first_place_is_my_talking_tom_app_hits_the_top_spot.aspx|publisher=Licensing Worldwide|accessdate=4 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=My Talking Tom: Review|url=http://omegadroid.co/talking-tom-coolest-cat-bigger-cuter/|publisher=OmegaDroid|accessdate=4 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Talking Tom and Friends'' YouTube channel has over 10 million<!-- please update the access-date of the reference after updating this --> subscribers and 3.5 billion views as of March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/TalkingFriends/about |title=Talking Tom and Friends|website=YouTube|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\nAs on April 2020, the franchise has had its apps downloaded more than 12 billion times.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://outfit7.com/press-page/|title=Outfit7 - Press page|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\nThe My Talking Tom app won the award for \"Best iPad Game: Kids, Education & Family\" at the 2014 Tabby Awards, the global competition for the best tablet app.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tabbyawards.com/2014winners/|title=The Tabby Awards 2014 Winners, Users' Choice and Finalists|work=tabbyawards.com|accessdate=6 April 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140904222432/http://tabbyawards.com/2014winners/|archivedate=4 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nMy Talking Tom was also voted the 2014 Tabby Award Users\u2019 Choice favorite in two categories, \"Best iPad Game: Kids, Education & Family\" and \"Best Android Game: Puzzle, Cards & Family\".<ref>{{cite web|title=My Talking Tom scoops Tabby Award|url=http://www.toyworldmag.co.uk/licensing-news/2014/08/my-talking-tom-scoops-tabby-award|publisher=ToyWorld|accessdate=4 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Talking Tom and Friends'' television series won the ''Best Animated Series'' Award at the 2016 Cablefax Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animationmagazine.net/events/counterfeit-cat-talking-tom-win-cablefax-awards/|title='Counterfeit Cat,' 'Talking Tom' Win Cablefax Awards|author=|date=8 August 2016|work=animationmagazine.net|accessdate=6 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of most downloaded Android applications]]\n* [[Digital puppetry]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://talkingtomandfriends.com}}\n\n[[Category:Talking Tom and Friends| ]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) software]]\n[[Category:IOS software]]\n[[Category:Video games adapted into television programs]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises introduced in 2010]]\n[[Category:Media franchises]]\n[[Category:Fictional cats]]\n", "name_user": "RedBulbBlueBlood9911", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added information", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Talking_Tom_and_Friends"}
{"title_page": "Escort Girls", "text_new": "{{short description|1974 film by Donovan Winter}}\n{{Distinguish|Escort Girl (film)}}\n{{Infobox film\n| image          = Escort girls.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = DVD cover\n| name                 = Escort Girls\n| director             = [[Donovan Winter]]\n| producer             = Donovan Winter\n| writer               = Donovan Winter\n| starring             = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Helen Christie]]\n*Marijke Mann\n*Barbara Wise\n*[[Brian Jackson (actor)|Brian Jackson]]\n}}\n| cinematography       = {{Plainlist|\n*Gus Coma\n*Austin Parkinson\n}}\n| editing              = Donovan Winter\n| production_companies = Donwin Productions\n| distributors         = Variety\n| released             = 1974\n| runtime              = 95 minutes\n| country              = United Kingdom\n| language             = English\n}}\n'''''Escort Girls''''' is a 1974 [[sexploitation film]] written, produced and directed by [[Donovan Winter]] and starring [[Helen Christie]], [[Brian Jackson (actor)|Brian Jackson]], [[David Dixon]], [[Veronica Doran]] and [[David Brierly]]. Its [[working title]] was ''All Lovers Are Strangers''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b6963ea0b|title=''Escort Girls'' (1974)|work=bfi.org.uk|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|location=London, UK|accessdate=6 October 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006120152/https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b6963ea0b|archivedate=6 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nSet in London, the film tells six stories of people seeking companionship in the run-up to Christmas.\n\n*'''Hugh and Susan''' ([[David Dixon]] and Maria O'Brien): Hugh, a young office clerk, spends his Christmas bonus on a night out with Susan, a [[social escort]]. After dinner at an Italian restaurant, they take a taxi back to Susan's flat, where both admit their loneliness. Susan takes Hugh's virginity.\n*'''Mary and Barry''' ([[Helen Christie]] and Richard Wren): Mary is a wealthy widow whose outward pride conceals her inner loneliness. She takes a young [[male escort]], Barry, to a nightclub and then back to her hotel room. Barry is put off by Mary's overbearing nature and slips away while her back is turned, leaving her heartbroken.\n*'''Emma and Wayne''' (Marijke Mann and Gil Barber): Emma is a company director weary of the business world. As an amusement, she hires a male escort, Wayne, to accompany her to a high-level Christmas party. Returning to Emma's house, Emma and Wayne have sex.\n*'''Harvey and Sheila''' ([[Brian Jackson (actor)|Brian Jackson]] and Barbara Wise): Harvey Matelow is a corrupt businessman who books an escort, Sheila, to take with him to a casino. Later, he tricks his way into her flat and rapes her. He is interrupted by Sheila's boyfriend (Max Mason), who photographs him in the act and proceeds to blackmail him, stealing his money and threatening to publish the photographs if he goes to the police. Realising that he has been set up, the humiliated Harvey is kicked out of the flat. Left alone, Sheila and the boyfriend have sex.\n*'''Vicky and Lester''' ([[Veronica Doran]] and Ken Gajadhar): To impress her old school friends, Vicky shows up at a reunion accompanied by Lester, a black male escort who has agreed to pose as her fianc\u00e9. Over the course of the party, Vicky's female friends fantasise about Lester and discreetly pass him their telephone numbers. Back at Vicky's flat, Lester hesitantly indulges Vicky's interracial [[rape fantasy]].\n*'''James and Ian''' ([[David Brierly]] and James Hunter): James and Ian are Scotsmen visiting London for the first time. They pick up two women and take them to dinner at a restaurant, where they are shocked to see an exotic dancer (Teresa Van Ross) give an explicit solo [[sex show]]. Later, they pursue the two women for sex but are knocked to the ground and drunkenly pass out.\n\nIn the film's epilogue, the normally shy and reserved Hugh arrives at work and greets his female colleagues by cheerfully slapping one of them on the rear with his morning newspaper.\n\n==Critical response==\n[[Gavin Millar]] of ''[[The Listener (magazine)|The Listener]]'' gave the film one star out of four. Reviews in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' and ''[[The Guardian]]'' were negative.<ref name=\"MFB\">{{Cite magazine |magazine=[[The Monthly Film Bulletin]] |title=5 Critics on the Month's Films |date=December 1974 |editor1-last=Combs |editor1-first=Richard |publisher=British Film Institute |location=London, UK |volume=41 |issue=491 |oclc=2594020 |issn=0027-0407 }} Back cover.</ref>\n\nRichard Combs of ''[[The Monthly Film Bulletin]]'' described ''Escort Girls'' as a \"sexploiter with pretensions\" whose acting \"is better than might be expected.\" He added that Winter \"profitably pays as much attention to all the background flummery of the social settings ... as he does to the walking clich\u00e9s who inhabit them.\"<ref>{{Cite magazine |magazine=The Monthly Film Bulletin |title=''Escort Girls'' |date=June 1974 |last=Combs |first=Richard |editor1-last=Combs |editor1-first=Richard |publisher=British Film Institute |location=London, UK |pages=124-125 |volume=41 |issue=485 |oclc=2594020 |issn=0027-0407}}</ref>\n\n[[Duncan Fallowell]] of ''[[The Spectator]]'' questioned the choice of title, pointing out that the film features both [[Female escort|female]] and [[male escort]]s. He commented: \"This may not be a withering triumph of cinematic art, but it is certainly a sight better than most of the films into whose bag it has been put ... The stories do have point \u2013 not much, perhaps, but what there is you do get \u2013 and it does add up to more than an excuse for titillation. Also I chuckled a lot, if that is any recommendation.\"<ref>{{Cite magazine|magazine=[[The Spectator]]|title=Cinema: Doing It To Death|last1=Fallowell|first1=Duncan|author1-link=Duncan Fallowell|date=16 November 1974|issn=0038-6952|oclc=1766325|page=636-637}}</ref>\n\nIn his introduction to [[Nucleus Films]]' 2011 DVD release of ''Escort Girls'', Darius Drewe praised the film as Winter's best demonstration of his \"multi-layered\", \"singular\" vision. He suggested that while the film touches on themes of realism and loneliness, certain elements, such as the story of Emma and Wayne, are more about \"how sometimes life is neither tragedy nor fairy tale, just matter-of-factly unremarkable.\" He criticised the pacing, commenting that the plot \"seems to amble sexlessly for 60 minutes before remembering what film it's in and suddenly jumping to several consecutive scenes of softcore action.\" He compared the structure of the film \u2013 \"a series of vignettes\" \u2013 to that of the comedy drama ''[[Saturday Night Out]]'' (1964).<ref>{{Cite AV media notes |title=It'll Be Lonely This Christmas: An Exploration of ''Escort Girls'' |year=2011 |first=Darius |last=Drewe |publisher=[[Nucleus Films]] |type=DVD liner notes |id=NN0009 }}</ref>\n\nIn a review for the website The Spinning Image, Graeme Clark comments: \"Until the cast begin taking their clothes off, this is achingly slow, and you're not sure if it's meant to be a comedy or not, but things pick up when the mood turns to sleaze ... [All of the characters except Hugh] ... come across as pretty strange, illustrating the gap between the sophistication it aspired to and the rather sour, seedy reality it ended up as.\"<ref>{{Cite web|title=''Escort Girls'' Review (1975)|last1=Clark|first1=Graeme|work=thespinningimage.co.uk|url= http://www.thespinningimage.co.uk/cultfilms/displaycultfilm.asp?reviewid=6526|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108013055/http://www.thespinningimage.co.uk/cultfilms/displaycultfilm.asp?reviewid=6526|archivedate=8 November 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nCommentator Leon Hunt considers ''Escort Girls'' to be one of a number of films that he dubs \"suburban report\" features: films employing a \"multiple narrative\" built around a \"thematic focus\" (in this case, characters' use of escorts) \"and/or a narrator, storyteller or 'expert' to guide us through\". He suggests that the virginal character David roots the film's impression of \"suburban sensibility\" in ideas of a \"last sexual outpost\" or \"notion of 'catching up', a sort of sexual democracy.\"<ref>{{Cite book |title=British Low Culture: from Safari Suits to Sexploitation |last1=Hunt |first1=Leon |publisher=[[Routledge]] |location=London, UK; New York City, New York |year=1998 |isbn=9781136189432 |pages=94, 106}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0262402}}\n*[https://www.hotelescortservices.com/ Escort girls in Jaipur]\n\n[[Category:1970s Christmas films]]\n[[Category:1970s exploitation films]]\n[[Category:1970s independent films]]\n[[Category:1974 films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British Christmas films]]\n[[Category:British exploitation films]]\n[[Category:British independent films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about male prostitution]]\n[[Category:Films about prostitution in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:Sexploitation films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1974 film by Donovan Winter}}\n{{Distinguish|Escort Girl (film)}}\n{{Infobox film\n| image          = Escort girls.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = DVD cover\n| name                 = Escort Girls\n| director             = [[Donovan Winter]]\n| producer             = Donovan Winter\n| writer               = Donovan Winter\n| starring             = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Helen Christie]]\n*Marijke Mann\n*Barbara Wise\n*[[Brian Jackson (actor)|Brian Jackson]]\n}}\n| cinematography       = {{Plainlist|\n*Gus Coma\n*Austin Parkinson\n}}\n| editing              = Donovan Winter\n| production_companies = Donwin Productions\n| distributors         = Variety\n| released             = 1974\n| runtime              = 95 minutes\n| country              = United Kingdom\n| language             = English\n}}\n'''''Escort Girls''''' is a 1974 [[sexploitation film]] written, produced and directed by [[Donovan Winter]] and starring [[Helen Christie]], [[Brian Jackson (actor)|Brian Jackson]], [[David Dixon]], [[Veronica Doran]] and [[David Brierly]]. Its [[working title]] was ''All Lovers Are Strangers''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b6963ea0b|title=''Escort Girls'' (1974)|work=bfi.org.uk|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|location=London, UK|accessdate=6 October 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006120152/https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b6963ea0b|archivedate=6 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nSet in London, the film tells six stories of people seeking companionship in the run-up to Christmas.\n\n*'''Hugh and Susan''' ([[David Dixon]] and Maria O'Brien): Hugh, a young office clerk, spends his Christmas bonus on a night out with Susan, a [[social escort]]. After dinner at an Italian restaurant, they take a taxi back to Susan's flat, where both admit their loneliness. Susan takes Hugh's virginity.\n*'''Mary and Barry''' ([[Helen Christie]] and Richard Wren): Mary is a wealthy widow whose outward pride conceals her inner loneliness. She takes a young [[male escort]], Barry, to a nightclub and then back to her hotel room. Barry is put off by Mary's overbearing nature and slips away while her back is turned, leaving her heartbroken.\n*'''Emma and Wayne''' (Marijke Mann and Gil Barber): Emma is a company director weary of the business world. As an amusement, she hires a male escort, Wayne, to accompany her to a high-level Christmas party. Returning to Emma's house, Emma and Wayne have sex.\n*'''Harvey and Sheila''' ([[Brian Jackson (actor)|Brian Jackson]] and Barbara Wise): Harvey Matelow is a corrupt businessman who books an escort, Sheila, to take with him to a casino. Later, he tricks his way into her flat and rapes her. He is interrupted by Sheila's boyfriend (Max Mason), who photographs him in the act and proceeds to blackmail him, stealing his money and threatening to publish the photographs if he goes to the police. Realising that he has been set up, the humiliated Harvey is kicked out of the flat. Left alone, Sheila and the boyfriend have sex.\n*'''Vicky and Lester''' ([[Veronica Doran]] and Ken Gajadhar): To impress her old school friends, Vicky shows up at a reunion accompanied by Lester, a black male escort who has agreed to pose as her fianc\u00e9. Over the course of the party, Vicky's female friends fantasise about Lester and discreetly pass him their telephone numbers. Back at Vicky's flat, Lester hesitantly indulges Vicky's interracial [[rape fantasy]].\n*'''James and Ian''' ([[David Brierly]] and James Hunter): James and Ian are Scotsmen visiting London for the first time. They pick up two women and take them to dinner at a restaurant, where they are shocked to see an exotic dancer (Teresa Van Ross) give an explicit solo [[sex show]]. Later, they pursue the two women for sex but are knocked to the ground and drunkenly pass out.\n\nIn the film's epilogue, the normally shy and reserved Hugh arrives at work and greets his female colleagues by cheerfully slapping one of them on the rear with his morning newspaper.\n\n==Critical response==\n[[Gavin Millar]] of ''[[The Listener (magazine)|The Listener]]'' gave the film one star out of four. Reviews in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' and ''[[The Guardian]]'' were negative.<ref name=\"MFB\">{{Cite magazine |magazine=[[The Monthly Film Bulletin]] |title=5 Critics on the Month's Films |date=December 1974 |editor1-last=Combs |editor1-first=Richard |publisher=British Film Institute |location=London, UK |volume=41 |issue=491 |oclc=2594020 |issn=0027-0407 }} Back cover.</ref>\n\nRichard Combs of ''[[The Monthly Film Bulletin]]'' described ''Escort Girls'' as a \"sexploiter with pretensions\" whose acting \"is better than might be expected.\" He added that Winter \"profitably pays as much attention to all the background flummery of the social settings ... as he does to the walking clich\u00e9s who inhabit them.\"<ref>{{Cite magazine |magazine=The Monthly Film Bulletin |title=''Escort Girls'' |date=June 1974 |last=Combs |first=Richard |editor1-last=Combs |editor1-first=Richard |publisher=British Film Institute |location=London, UK |pages=124-125 |volume=41 |issue=485 |oclc=2594020 |issn=0027-0407}}</ref>\n\n[[Duncan Fallowell]] of ''[[The Spectator]]'' questioned the choice of title, pointing out that the film features both [[Female escort|female]] and [[male escort]]s. He commented: \"This may not be a withering triumph of cinematic art, but it is certainly a sight better than most of the films into whose bag it has been put ... The stories do have point \u2013 not much, perhaps, but what there is you do get \u2013 and it does add up to more than an excuse for titillation. Also I chuckled a lot, if that is any recommendation.\"<ref>{{Cite magazine|magazine=[[The Spectator]]|title=Cinema: Doing It To Death|last1=Fallowell|first1=Duncan|author1-link=Duncan Fallowell|date=16 November 1974|issn=0038-6952|oclc=1766325|page=636-637}}</ref>\n\nIn his introduction to [[Nucleus Films]]' 2011 DVD release of ''Escort Girls'', Darius Drewe praised the film as Winter's best demonstration of his \"multi-layered\", \"singular\" vision. He suggested that while the film touches on themes of realism and loneliness, certain elements, such as the story of Emma and Wayne, are more about \"how sometimes life is neither tragedy nor fairy tale, just matter-of-factly unremarkable.\" He criticised the pacing, commenting that the plot \"seems to amble sexlessly for 60 minutes before remembering what film it's in and suddenly jumping to several consecutive scenes of softcore action.\" He compared the structure of the film \u2013 \"a series of vignettes\" \u2013 to that of the comedy drama ''[[Saturday Night Out]]'' (1964).<ref>{{Cite AV media notes |title=It'll Be Lonely This Christmas: An Exploration of ''Escort Girls'' |year=2011 |first=Darius |last=Drewe |publisher=[[Nucleus Films]] |type=DVD liner notes |id=NN0009 }}</ref>\n\nIn a review for the website The Spinning Image, Graeme Clark comments: \"Until the cast begin taking their clothes off, this is achingly slow, and you're not sure if it's meant to be a comedy or not, but things pick up when the mood turns to sleaze ... [All of the characters except Hugh] ... come across as pretty strange, illustrating the gap between the sophistication it aspired to and the rather sour, seedy reality it ended up as.\"<ref>{{Cite web|title=''Escort Girls'' Review (1975)|last1=Clark|first1=Graeme|work=thespinningimage.co.uk|url= http://www.thespinningimage.co.uk/cultfilms/displaycultfilm.asp?reviewid=6526|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108013055/http://www.thespinningimage.co.uk/cultfilms/displaycultfilm.asp?reviewid=6526|archivedate=8 November 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nCommentator Leon Hunt considers ''Escort Girls'' to be one of a number of films that he dubs \"suburban report\" features: films employing a \"multiple narrative\" built around a \"thematic focus\" (in this case, characters' use of escorts) \"and/or a narrator, storyteller or 'expert' to guide us through\". He suggests that the virginal character David roots the film's impression of \"suburban sensibility\" in ideas of a \"last sexual outpost\" or \"notion of 'catching up', a sort of sexual democracy.\"<ref>{{Cite book |title=British Low Culture: from Safari Suits to Sexploitation |last1=Hunt |first1=Leon |publisher=[[Routledge]] |location=London, UK; New York City, New York |year=1998 |isbn=9781136189432 |pages=94, 106}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0262402}}\n\n[[Category:1970s Christmas films]]\n[[Category:1970s exploitation films]]\n[[Category:1970s independent films]]\n[[Category:1974 films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British Christmas films]]\n[[Category:British exploitation films]]\n[[Category:British independent films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about male prostitution]]\n[[Category:Films about prostitution in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:Sexploitation films]]\n", "name_user": "Genuinehotelescorts", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Escort_Girls"}
{"title_page": "The Junior Defenders", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = The Junior Defenders\n| image =\n| alt =\n| caption =\n| director = Keith Spiegel\n| producer = Keith Spiegel<br />[[Brooke Ciardelli]]\n| writer = Keith Spiegel\n| narrator = [[John Waters (filmmaker)|John Waters]]\n| starring = [[Ally Sheedy]]<br />[[Brian O'Halloran]]<br />[[Justin Henry]]<br />[[Jason David Frank]]<br />Fred Hazelton\n| cinematography = Mark Sasahara\n| editing = Keith Spiegel<br />Rick Giachino<br />Stephen Beattie\n| studio = [[Lightyear Entertainment]]\n| distributor = [[Warner Bros.|Warner Home Video]]\n| released = {{Film date|2007|10|23}}\n| runtime = 82 minutes\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| budget = $172,000{{Citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n}}\n'''''The Junior Defenders''''' is a 2007 [[direct-to-video]] [[comedy film|comedy]]-[[fantasy film]] from [[Warner Bros.]] starring [[Ally Sheedy]], [[Brian O'Halloran]], [[Justin Henry]], and [[Jason David Frank]].\n\n==Plot==\nWith a fanbase that rivaled ''[[Star Trek]]''{{'}}s, ''The Junior Defenders'' was one of the top TV hits of the late '70s. 25 years following the show's sudden cancellation, a crazed fan named Norman is still obsessed with the show. In his mania, Norman treks across the country in a stolen [[Winnebago Industries|Winnebago]], kidnapping the four washed-up former child stars, Jill, Mitch, Jimmy, and Tommy, from his beloved childhood program. The kidnappings spark a national media frenzy. Once in Hollywood, Norman takes over a [[soundstage]] and forces the cast at gunpoint to act in his brand-new episode of ''The Junior Defenders''.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[John Waters (filmmaker)|John Waters]] as Narrator\n* [[Ally Sheedy]] as Jill Fields\n* [[Brian O'Halloran]] as Mitch Stone\n* [[Justin Henry]] as Jimmy Fletcher\n* [[Jason David Frank]] as Tommy Keen \n* Fred Hazelton as Norman Nields\n\nThe film features [[cameo appearance]]s by [[Pauly Shore]], [[Florence Henderson]], [[Peter Tork]], [[Michael Dukakis]], and [[Kevin Smith]].\n\n==Production==\nOriginally titled ''Groupies'', the film's [[principal photography]] occurred in February\u2013March 1997.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.viewaskew.com/interviews/briano2.html |title=Interview with Brian O'Halloran| publisher=[[View Askew Productions|View Askew]]| date=February 2, 1998| accessdate=2009-02-14}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.juniordefenders.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|0119231|The Junior Defenders}}\n* {{allrovi movie|413370|The Junior Defenders}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|the-junior-defenders|The Junior Defenders}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Junior Defenders}}\n[[Category:2007 direct-to-video films]]\n[[Category:2000s fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1970s]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2003]]\n[[Category:American independent films]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros. films]]\n\n\n{{2000s-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = The Junior Defenders\n| image =\n| alt =\n| caption =\n| director = Keith Spiegel\n| producer = Keith Spiegel<br />[[Brooke Ciardelli]]\n| writer = Keith Spiegel\n| narrator = [[John Waters (filmmaker)|John Waters]]\n| starring = [[Ally Sheedy]]<br />[[Brian O'Halloran]]<br />[[Justin Henry]]<br />[[Jason David Frank]]<br />Fred Hazelton\n| cinematography = Mark Sasahara\n| editing = Keith Spiegel<br />Rick Giachino<br />Stephen Beattie\n| studio = [[Lightyear Entertainment]]\n| distributor = [[Warner Bros.|Warner Home Video]]\n| released = {{Film date|2007|10|23}}\n| runtime = 82 minutes\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| budget = $172,000{{Citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n}}\n'''''The Junior Defenders''''' is a 2007 [[direct-to-video]] [[comedy film|comedy]]-[[fantasy film]] from [[Warner Bros.]] starring [[Ally Sheedy]], [[Brian O'Halloran]], [[Justin Henry]], and [[Jason David Frank]].\n\n==Plot==\nWith a fanbase that rivaled ''[[Star Trek]]''{{'}}s, ''The Junior Defenders'' was one of the top TV hits of the late '70s. 25 years following the show's sudden cancellation, a crazed fan named Norman is still obsessed with the show. In his mania, Norman treks across the country in a stolen [[Winnebago Industries|Winnebago]], kidnapping the four washed-up former child stars, Jill, Mitch, Jimmy, and Tommy, from his beloved childhood program. The kidnappings spark a national media frenzy. Once in Hollywood, Norman takes over a [[soundstage]] and forces the cast at gunpoint to act in his brand-new episode of ''The Junior Defenders''.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[John Waters (filmmaker)|John Waters]] as Narrator\n* [[Ally Sheedy]] as Jill Fields\n* [[Brian O'Halloran]] as Mitch Stone\n* [[Justin Henry]] as Jimmy Fletcher\n* [[Jason David Frank]] as Tommy Keen \n* Fred Hazelton as Norman Nields\n\nThe film features [[cameo appearance]]s by [[Pauly Shore]], [[Florence Henderson]], [[Peter Tork]], [[Michael Dukakis]], and [[Kevin Smith]].\n\n==Production==\nOriginally titled ''Groupies'', the film's [[principal photography]] occurred in February\u2013March 1997.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.viewaskew.com/interviews/briano2.html |title=Interview with Brian O'Halloran| publisher=[[View Askew Productions|View Askew]]| date=February 2, 1998| accessdate=2009-02-14}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.juniordefenders.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|1099971|The Junior Defenders}}\n* {{allrovi movie|413370|The Junior Defenders}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|the-junior-defenders|The Junior Defenders}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Junior Defenders}}\n[[Category:2007 direct-to-video films]]\n[[Category:2000s fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films set 