{"title_page": "Sphecius grandis", "text_new": "{{Good article}}\n{{Speciesbox\n | image               = Western CKs mating.jpg \n | image_alt           = Two amber-yellow wasps, male above, female below, mate in some grass, tails touching.\n | image_caption       = Two ''Sphecius grandis'' wasps mate (male above, female below), in [[Big Bend (Texas)|Big Bend, Texas]].\n | taxon            = Sphecius grandis\n | authority  = ([[Thomas Say|Say]], 1823)<ref>{{cite journal | url=https://www.redalyc.org/pdf/575/57523304.pdf | title=Sphecidae y Crabronidae (Hymenoptera) \u2013 De algunos Municipios del Centro y Sur de Tamaulipas, M\u00e9xico | author=V\u00edctor, Jorge | journal=Acta Zool\u00f3gica Mexicana | year=2007 | volume=23 | issue=3 | pages=35\u201348 | url-status=live | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925021139/http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/pdf/575/57523304.pdf | archive-date=2012-09-25 | df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://essigdb.berkeley.edu/cgi/eme_query?bnhm_id=EMEC55413&one=T&OK2SHOWPRIVATE=1 | title=Detail of Catalog ID# EMEC55413 | publisher=Essig Museum of Entomology | date=December 6, 2004 | accessdate=August 15, 2011 | author=Nishida, Gordon}}</ref>\n | synonyms            = ''Stizus grandis'' <small>Say, 1823</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Sphecius grandis''''', also called the '''western cicada killer''', is a species of [[Sphecius|cicada killer wasp]] (''Sphecius''). The western species shares the same [[Nest|nesting biology]] as its fellow species, the eastern cicada killer (''[[Sphecius speciosus|S. speciosus]]''). ''S.&nbsp;grandis'', like all other species of the [[genus]] ''Sphecius'', mainly provides [[cicada]]s for its offspring. It forms nest aggregations and mates and [[Voltinism|broods once in a year]], in July and early August. The wasp is on average {{convert|3|cm|in|round=0.5|abbr=on}} to {{convert|5|cm|in|round=0.5|abbr=on}} in length and is amber-yellow with yellow rings on its [[abdomen]].\n\nWasps in the genus ''Sphecius'' are not habitually aggressive and use their [[venom]] mainly to paralyse cicadas which they take back to their nests to feed their young. The females catch around four or more cicadas for provisioning, place them in brood cells and lay eggs in the cells. ''S.&nbsp;grandis'' is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Central America]], Mexico and the [[Western United States]], and is found at a higher mean altitude than other species of ''Sphecius''. The western cicada killer males emerge earlier than females, but generally die after only a couple of days.\n\n''Sphecius grandis'' can be distinguished from ''S.&nbsp;convallis'' (the Pacific cicada killer wasp) by the coloration pattern of the gastral [[Tergum|tergites]]. Formerly, the two species were distinguished on the basis of the number of tergites with yellow markings (five in ''S.&nbsp;grandis'' and three in ''S.&nbsp;convallis''), but a more recent study showed that this character was insufficient to distinguish the two species. However, they can be distinguished by the density of the punctation on the first and second tergites.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe western cicada killer was first described by American naturalist [[Thomas Say]] in 1824 in [[Madera Canyon (Arizona)|Madera Canyon]], Arizona, as ''Stizus grandis''. Its species name is the [[Latin]] adjective ''grandis'' meaning \"large\". It is one of five species of the genus ''[[Sphecius]]'' in North America.<ref name=\"bionica\">{{cite journal | url=http://www.bio-nica.info/biblioteca/Holliday2006Sphecius.pdf | title=Improved Key to New World Species of Sphecius (Hymenoptera: Crabronidae |author1=Holliday, Charles W. |author2=Coelho, Joseph R. | journal=Annals of the Entomological Society of America | year=2006 | volume=99 | pages=793\u2013798 | doi=10.1603/0013-8746(2006)99[793:IKTNWS]2.0.CO;2 | issue=5}}</ref>\n\nMore recently, it has been suspected that the western cicada killer represents more than one species. It co-occurs with the eastern cicada killer (''S.&nbsp;speciosus'') and Pacific cicada killer (''S.&nbsp;convallis'') at [[Big Bend National Park]] in Texas. There the three wasps hunt and nest in the same locales, and the eastern and western cicada killers hunt the same cicada species. Analysis of [[mitochondrial DNA]] showed that the western cicada killer contains two divergent [[clade]]s, which may represent distinct species. The two clades appeared to be split by the [[Rocky Mountains]], with one occurring mainly to the south and east, the other to the west.<ref name=\"zoot\">{{cite journal|author1=Hastings, Jon M. |author2=Schultheis, Patrick J. |author3=Whitson, Maggie |author4=Holliday, Charles W. |author5=Coelho, Joseph R. |author6=Mendell, Angela M. |year=2008|title=DNA barcoding of new world cicada killers (Hymenoptera: Crabronidae)|journal=[[Zootaxa]]|volume=1713|pages=27\u201338|url=http://www.mapress.com/zootaxa/2008/f/zt01713p038.pdf|hdl=10385/598}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nRanging in size from {{convert|3|to|5|cm|in|round=0.5|abbr=on}} in length, the western cicada killer is very similar to its eastern cousin, ''[[Sphecius speciosus]]'', with a [[rufous]] black hue to the body, amber stripes and a yellow abdomen.<ref name=\"bionica\" /><ref>{{cite journal| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RsVLAAAAYAAJ&q=sphecius+grandis&dq=sphecius+grandis | title=Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia | journal=American Natural History | year=1901 | volume=53 | pages=788\u2013794 | author1=Philadelphia | first1=Academy of Natural Sciences of}}</ref><ref name=\"cdri\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cdri.org/fieldguides/wasps/taxonomy/robust-yellow-group.html | title=Wasps (Order: Hymenoptera) \u2013 Robust Yellow Group | publisher=[[Chihuahuan Desert Nature Center and Botanical Gardens]] | access-date=August 11, 2011 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927062046/http://www.cdri.org/fieldguides/wasps/taxonomy/robust-yellow-group.html | archive-date=September 27, 2011 | df= }}</ref> The western cicada killer has rufous spots on its first to second tergites and yellow markings can generally be found from first to fifth, although there is some variation.<ref name=\"bionica\" /> On average, female [[forewing]] length lies between {{convert|2.5|and|3|cm|in|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"jstor\" /> Females are larger than males and live for a year, a time just long enough to produce a brood, whereas the males die in only a few days, just enough time to impregnate a female.<ref name=\"cdri\" /> In Steven J. Phillips' book ''A Natural History of the Sonoran Desert'', he referred to them as superficially resembling \"huge yellowjackets or hornets\" and stated that they are \"powerful fliers with compound eyes\".<ref>[[#Phillips|Phillips (1999)]], p. 346</ref> On average, males weigh 95{{nbsp;}}[[Milligram|mg]] and females are far heavier, at 256{{nbsp;}}mg,<ref>[[#Vander Wall|Vander Wall (1990)]], p. 38</ref> probably because of the additional weight of the ovaries, developing eggs and nutritional reserves. Nevertheless, the ratio between flight muscle mass and body mass is the same for both sexes.<ref name=\"jspss\">{{cite journal| title=Sexual size dimorphism and flight behavior in cicada killers | author=Coelho, Joseph R. | journal=Oikos |date=June 1997 | volume=79 | issue=2 | pages=371\u2013375 | doi=10.2307/3546021 | jstor=3546021}}</ref>\n\n===Identification===\nDistinguishing ''S.&nbsp;grandis'' from the other four New World species of ''[[Sphecius]]'' (''[[Sphecius convallis|S.&nbsp;convallis]]'', ''[[Sphecius hogardii|S.&nbsp;hogardii]]'', ''[[Sphecius speciosus|S. speciosus]]'', ''[[Sphecius spectabilis|S.&nbsp;spectabilis]]'') is difficult. The female ''S.&nbsp;convallis'' was originally distinguished from the female ''S. grandis'' by the yellow marks from the first to third gastral [[Tergum|tergites]] on ''S.&nbsp;convallis'' and yellow marks on all tergites for ''S.&nbsp;grandis''. However, this was found to be insufficient for correct identification because the positions of the markings can vary among different wasps of the same species.<ref name=\"bionica\" />\n\nCharles W. Holliday and Joseph R. Coelho devised a new key in 2004 to identify the ''Sphecius'' species, examining 4,451 wasps among the five New World species, and noting that 98% of the female ''S. convallis'' wasps examined had yellow markings on gastral tergites one to four (or fewer) and ''S.&nbsp;grandis'' had 98% yellow markings from tergites one to five (or more). The 2% percent of ''S.&nbsp;grandis'' that overlapped with ''S.&nbsp;convallis'' were determined by density of the punctation in colour of the first tergum against the second. The markings on ''S.&nbsp;grandis'' males were found to be the same as on females.<ref name=\"bionica\" />\n\n===Thermoregulation===\nIt has been found that the western cicada killer wasp is capable of [[thermoregulation]] which enables them to maintain territories during the day.<ref name=\"sasi\" /> A study by Joseph R. Coelho showed that during territorial patrolling the species had a high and regulated [[Thorax (insect anatomy)|thorax]] temperature. Experiments found that the wasp has the ability to shift heat from its thorax to its abdomen and that the abdomen is generally kept colder than the thorax. Dead wasps that were placed in the sun reached abnormally high temperatures when compared to those on nearby plants.<ref name=\"scdir\">{{cite journal | title=Thermoregulation in male western cicada killers (''Sphecius grandis'' Say) in the Chihuahuan desert |author1=Coelho, Joseph R. |author2=Holliday, Charles W. |author3=Hastings, Jon. M. |author4=Maty, Elizabeth |author5=Swigart, Meghan |author6=Mendel, Angela | journal=Journal of Thermal Biology |date=July 2007 | volume=32 | issue=5 | pages=270\u2013275 | doi = 10.1016/j.jtherbio.2007.01.016 }}</ref>\n\n==Life cycle==\n\n===Emergence and mating===\nAfter [[Egg (biology)|hatching]], the offspring feed on the tissue of the cicadas provided by their mother. Males emerge before females and both genders are [[Sexual maturity|sexually receptive]] from emergence in July to early August, when they mate and brood. English naturalist [[Charles Darwin]] postulated that the pattern of male emergence before females evolved by [[natural selection]] to improve the chances of the male mating. The timing of the emergence of females has evolved to correspond with the similar emergence of the cicada species of the area, ''[[Tibicen|Tibicen duryi]]'' and ''T.&nbsp;parallela'', which they hunt for the provisioning of their nests.<ref name=\"jstor2\">{{cite journal |jstor=4600338 | title=Protandry in western cicada killer wasps (''Sphecius grandis'', Hymnoptera: Sphecidae) and empirical study of emergence time and mating opportunity | author=Hastings, Jon | journal=Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology |date=April 1989 | volume=25 | issue=4 | pages=255\u2013260 |doi=10.1007/BF00300051}}</ref> Many have yellow markings located on their [[Tergum|tergites]] ([[Anatomical terms of location#Dorsal and ventral|dorsal portion]]), although some have been found only from the first to fifth tergites.<ref name=\"bionica\"/>\n\n[[File:Cicada Killer Wasp.jpg|thumb|''[[Sphecius speciosus]]'' (eastern cicada killer) shares many behavioral similarities with ''Sphecius grandis''.]]\nBecause males emerge earlier than females, the males compete for mating territories surrounding the nests in which the females are located. During a fight, the males risk damaging their wings or appendages by butting and grappling.<ref name=\"sandwas2\">[[#Evans|Evans (2007)]], p. 35</ref> Another defense technique is to grab another male and carry it high into the air, which is thought to be a demonstration of strength. As a general rule, the larger the male the more predominant he is in battles.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Hastings, Jon |year=1990 |title=Sexual-size dimorphism in Western cicada killer wasps, ''Sphecius grandis'' (Hymenoptera: Sphecidae) |journal=Transactions of the Kentucky Academy of Science |volume=50 |issue=1\u20132 |pages=1\u20135 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/104927#page/261/mode/1up}}</ref> Age influences the success in the defense and security of territory; the younger the wasp the greater the chance of a successful takeover of territory. Some small males even engage in non-territorial mating tactics,<ref name=\"jsps2\">{{cite journal | title=The Influence of Size, Age and Residency Status in Territory Defense in Male Western Cicada Killer Wasps (''Sphecius grandis'', Hymenoptera: Sphecidae) | author=Hastings, Jon M. | journal=Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society |date=July 1989 | volume=62 | issue=3 | pages=363\u2013373 | jstor=25085103}}</ref> and delay their emergence so as to have a fairer chance of survival.<ref name=\"ox\">{{cite journal | url=http://beheco.oxfordjournals.org/content/13/3/337.full | title=Protandry models and their application to salmon | author=Morbey, Yoland E. | journal=Behavioral Ecology |date=June 2001 | volume=13 | issue=3 | pages=337\u2013343 | doi=10.1093/beheco/13.3.337| citeseerx=10.1.1.555.6866 }}</ref>\n\nOn emergence from the nest, the female is sexually receptive but does not choose her mate, but instead [[copulation (zoology)|copulates]] with the first male of her species that finds her.<ref name=\"jstor2\" /> Once the female has mated, she rebuffs all advances by other wasps.\n\n===Nesting and perching===\nMales perch after emerging from their nest. They pick out an area close to a nest with females inside and guard the territory around it so as to have a better chance of mating. They tend to perch on many different [[Substrate (biology)|substrates]] such as stumps, pebbles, wood, weeds, grass blades and low tree branches. Males assume an alert posture, ready for a challenge from another male, or from a predator. One study by a [[Behavioral ecology|behavioral ecologist]], [[John Alcock (behavioral ecologist)|John Alcock]], showed that a large majority of the marked wasps returned to the same perch day after day, and two males swapped between two different sites.<ref name=\"tand\">{{cite journal | title=The behaviour of western cicada killer males, ''Sphecius grandis'' (Sphecidae, Hymenoptera) | author=Alcock, John | journal=[[Journal of Natural History]] | year=1975 | volume=9 | issue=5 | pages=561\u2013566 |doi=10.1080/00222937500770431}}</ref> The species rarely perches on the ground.<ref name=\"scdir\" />\n\nIt shares the same [[Nest|nesting biology]] as ''S.&nbsp;speciosus''.<ref name=\"jstor\">{{cite journal |jstor=25084766 | title=Provisioning by female Western cicada killer wasps, ''Sphecius grandis'' (Hymnoptera: Sphecidae): influence of body size and emergence time on individual provisioning success | author=Hastings, Jon | journal=[[Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society]] |date=April 1986 | volume=59 | issue=2 | pages=262\u2013268}}</ref> All [[Sphecius|cicada killers]] are ground-nesting insects and nest aggregations can contain up to hundreds of nests, each with a single provisioning female.<ref name=\"zoot\" /> Their tunnel is mainly made in well-drained, bare sandy soil,<ref name=\"kentu\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ca.uky.edu/entomology/entfacts/ef004.asp | title=Cicada Killer Wasps | publisher=[[University of Kentucky]] | year=2010 | accessdate=August 23, 2011 | author=Townsend, Lee}}</ref> frequently under sidewalks,<ref name=\"natu\" /> but is generally in full sunlight. Approximately 90% of its life is spent underground as a larva.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://sites.lafayette.edu/hollidac/research/biology-of-cicada-killer-wasps/ | title=Biology of cicada killer wasps | publisher=[[Lafayette College]] | date=November 16, 2009 | accessdate=August 15, 2011 | author=Kosmeier, Dieter}}</ref> It rarely infests grounds that are rich in vegetation in order for them to get more sun. Mounds are easily recognizable by their distinctive U-shaped digging entrance.<ref name=\"kentu\" />\n\n===Feeding and hunting habits===\n''Sphecius grandis'' has very similar nesting and feeding habits to other members of its genus, most notably ''Sphecius speciosus''.<ref name=\"jstor\" /><ref name=\"jstor2\" /> As with ''S.&nbsp;speciosus'',<ref>{{cite web | url=http://entomology.ifas.ufl.edu/creatures/beneficial/cicada_killers.htm | title=Cicada killers | publisher=[[Florida Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services]] | date=June 2003 | accessdate=August 11, 2011 | author=Stange, Lionel A.}}</ref> the female hunts for [[cicada]]s in low tree trunks, helped by the calls of the cicada males, and paralyses the insect by piercing the [[central nervous system]] with her [[stinger]].<ref name=\"kentu\" /><ref name=\"natu\">{{cite journal | url=http://www.nature.nps.gov/views/KCs/SonoranDesert/Media/Documents/JUNTOS_EnglishPDFs/Juntosengunit2.pdf | title=A Dynamic Balance Living in the Sonoran Desert | author=Zolinas, Zachary | journal=Juntos, Unit Two | year=1999 | pages=12}}</ref> She drags the cicadas back to her nest to place them in brood cells in which she eventually lays one egg per cell.<ref name=\"jstor\" /> Females carry cicadas that are on average 88% heavier than their own body mass. It has been hypothesised that cicada killers may also have the ability to capture cicadas mid-flight.<ref name=\"jspss\" /> There are approximately two or more cicadas to each brood cell.<ref name=\"jstor\" /><ref name=\"kentu\" /> When the larvae hatch, the cicada provides nutrition for the offspring to feed on.<ref name=\"jstor\" />\n\nThe wasps preferentially hunt for female cicadas because they have more consumable tissue, but male cicadas are easier to locate, which explains the systemic bias towards male kills.<ref name=\"bioo\">{{cite journal |author1=Holliday, Charles W. |author2=Hastings, Jon M. |author3=Coelho, Joseph R. |year=2009 |title=Cicada prey of New World cicada killers, ''Sphecius'' spp. (Dahlbom, 1843) (Hymenoptera: Crabronidae) |journal=Entomological News |volume=120 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201317 |doi=10.3157/021.120.0101}}</ref> They chiefly hunt for ''[[Tibicen duryi]]'', ''[[Tibicen dealbata]]'' and ''[[Tibicen parallela]]''.<ref>{{cite journal | url=http://www.fcla.edu/FlaEnt/fe91p657.pdf | title=Body Size Relationship Between Sphecius speciosus (Hymenoptera: Crabronidae) and their Prey: Prey Size Determines Wasp Size |author1=Coelho, Joseph R. |author2=Holliday, Charles W. |author3=Hastings, Jon M. | journal=Florida Entomologist |date=December 2008 | volume=91 | issue=4 | pages=657\u2013663 | doi=10.1653/0015-4040-91.4.657 }}</ref><ref name=\"sandwas\" /> Cicada killers are capable of [[thermoregulation]], which allows them to hunt for cicadas during the day, when the cicadas are most prominent.<ref name=\"sasi\">{{cite conference | url=http://www.sasionline.org/instar/Instar42.pdf | title=The 17th Annual IECC Conference | publisher=[[Sonoran Arthropod Studies Institute|SASI]] | accessdate=August 15, 2011 | author=Olson, Carl A.| booktitle=SASI's Communication Quarterly | year=2009 | conference=The 17th Annual IECC Conference | pages=8}}</ref> The species is mostly harmless to humans.<ref name=\"natu\" /> Some males when emerging early fly into the trees to feed on [[sap]],<ref name=\"tand\" /> and the species has been known to feed on [[nectar]].<ref name=\"kentu\" /><ref name=\"bios\">{{cite journal | url=http://biostor.org/reference/80292 | title=Territoriality and mating behavior of ''Sphex pensylvanicus'' L. (Hymenoptera: Sphecidae) | author=Kurczewski, F. E. | journal=Journal of Hymenoptera Research | year=1998 | volume=7 | issue=1 | pages=74\u201383}}</ref>\n\nStings of this species received a lethality rating of 46&nbsp;LC measured by LC={{frac|\u03bcg|LD<sub>50</sub>}} (LC=\"lethal capacity\", \u03bcg=\"venom in the insect\", LD<sub>50</sub>=\"{{frac|\u03bcg|g}} of the venom\", g=\"size of mammal receiving the dose\" and LD=\"lethal dose\").<ref>[[#Resh|Resh (2009)]], p. 1030</ref><ref name=\"scfa\" />\n\n==Geographical distribution==\nWestern cicada killers are found at a higher altitude than most other ''Sphecius'' species and are [[sympatry|sympatric]] with the species ''S.&nbsp;convallis'' and ''S.&nbsp;speciosus'', even though ''S.&nbsp;grandis'' are on average found at higher altitudes than ''S.&nbsp;convallis''. A study showed that the mean elevation for ''S.&nbsp;grandis'' was 755&nbsp;[[metre|m]] \u00b1 23.3&nbsp;m, compared with the lower results of ''S.&nbsp;speciosus'' (219&nbsp;m \u00b1 4.7&nbsp;m), ''S.&nbsp;convallis'' (582&nbsp;m \u00b1 30.9&nbsp;m) and ''S.&nbsp;hogardii'' (18&nbsp;m \u00b1 5&nbsp;m).<ref name=\"benth\">{{cite journal | url=http://www.benthamscience.com/open/toentoj/articles/V005/31TOENTOJ.pdf | title=The Geographic Distributions of Cicada Killers (''Sphecius''; Hymenoptera, Crabronidae) in the America | author1=Coelho, Joseph R. | author2=Holliday, Charles W. | author3=Hastings, Jon M. | journal=The Open Entomology Journal | date=March 2011 | volume=5 | pages=31\u201338 | doi=10.2174/1874407901105010031 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401201002/http://www.benthamscience.com/open/toentoj/articles/V005/31TOENTOJ.pdf | archive-date=2012-04-01 | df= }}</ref> The species is [[Nearctic ecozone|Nearctic]] and [[Neotropic ecozone|Neotropic]], found from [[Central America]] to the [[Western United States]],<ref name=\"sandwas\">[[#Evans|Evans (2007)]], p. 34</ref> in [[New Mexico]], [[California]] and every state west of the [[Rocky Mountains]], except [[Wyoming]], as well as [[Kansas]], [[Oklahoma]] and [[Nebraska]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://aces.nmsu.edu/academics/arthropods/spotlight-specimens-in-t.html | title=Spotlight Specimens in the Museum | publisher=[[New Mexico State University]] | year=2008 | access-date=August 23, 2011 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007015948/http://aces.nmsu.edu/academics/arthropods/spotlight-specimens-in-t.html | archive-date=October 7, 2011 | df= }}</ref><ref name=\"hydr\" /> ''S.&nbsp;grandis'' is most commonly found in [[riparian zones]]. It has been observed in such places in Mexico as [[Baja California Norte]], [[Baja California Sur]], [[Coahuila]], [[Nuevo Leon]], [[Tamaulipas]] and [[Yucat\u00e1n (state)|Yucat\u00e1n]] and also in [[Granada, Nicaragua|Granada]] ([[Nicaragua]]), [[Guanacaste Province|Guanacaste]] ([[Costa Rica]]) and [[Honduras]].<ref name=\"benth\" />\n\n==Interaction with humans==\n''Sphecius grandis'' wasps frequently interact with humans because of their tendency to make their nests in backyards, gardens and sidewalks.<ref name=\"natu\" /> Pest control is mostly unneeded as they nest in areas with little to no vegetation, usually ignore people, and females are not aggressive, tending to save their venom for their cicada prey,<ref name=\"cdri\" /> but will sting if they are grabbed or stepped on.<ref name=\"kentu\" /><ref name=\"hydr\" /><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.masterbeekeeper.org/stinging/cicadakiller.htm | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050306001320/http://www.masterbeekeeper.org/stinging/cicadakiller.htm | url-status=dead | archive-date=2005-03-06 | title=Stinging Insects: Cicada Killer Wasps | publisher=Masterbeekeeper.org | work=Dyce Laboratory for Honey Bee Studies | date=July 2004 | access-date=August 23, 2011 | author=Gardner, Kathryn }}</ref> Despite their large size, being the largest wasp to inhabit California,<ref name=\"hydr\">{{cite web | url=http://www.hydrex.info/cicada-killer-wasp/ | title=Cicada Killer Wasp | publisher=Hydrex Pest Control | accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> their sting has been reported as being between merely numbing and sharp to moderate.<ref name=\"scfa\">{{cite journal | url=https://www.scfaz.com/content/downloadable_materials/dealing_wBugs1.pdf | title=Pain Ratings of Solitary Wasps | author=Conniff, Richard | journal=Prescription Treatment Quarterly | date=April 2002 | volume=21 | issue=1 | pages=1\u201318 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320005139/https://www.scfaz.com/content/downloadable_materials/dealing_wBugs1.pdf | archive-date=2012-03-20 | df= }}</ref><ref name=\"cals\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cals.uidaho.edu/edComm/pdf/BUL/BUL0853.pdf | title=Homeowner Guide to Minor Stinging Insects | publisher=[[University of Idaho]] | date=May 2009 | accessdate=August 17, 2011 | pages=1\u20138}}</ref> Males, while smaller, are naturally more aggressive and less tolerant of disturbance.<ref name=\"kentu\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|32em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book | title=The Sand Wasps: Natural History and Behavior | url=https://archive.org/details/sandwaspsnatural0000evan | url-access=registration | publisher=[[Harvard University Press]] | author=Evans, Ensign Howard |author2=Kevin M. O'Neill |year=2007 | isbn=978-0-674-02462-5 |ref=Evans}}\n* {{cite book | title=Encyclopedia of Insects | publisher=[[Elsevier]] | author=Resh, Vincent H. | author2=Card\u00e9, Ring T. | year=2009 | isbn=978-0-12-586990-4 | ref=Resh | url-access=registration | url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofin00bada }}\n* {{cite book | title=A Natural History of the Sonoran Desert | author=Phillips, Steven J. | author2=Comus, Patricia Wentworth | year=1999 | isbn=978-0-520-21980-9 | publisher=[[Arizona-Sonora Desert Museum]] | ref=Phillips | url-access=registration | url=https://archive.org/details/naturalhistoryof00ariz }}\n* {{cite book | title=Food hoarding in animals | url=https://archive.org/details/foodhoardinginan0000vand | url-access=registration |author1=Vander Wall |author2=Stephen B. | year=1990 |isbn=978-0-226-84735-1 |publisher =[[University of Chicago Press]] | ref=Vander Wall}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Sphecius grandis}}\n{{Portal|Insects}}\n* ''[http://www.discoverlife.org/mp/20q?search=Sphecius+grandis Sphecius grandis]'' at Discover Life\n* ''[http://zipcodezoo.com/Animals/S/Sphecius_grandis/ Sphecius grandis]'' at ZipcodeZoo\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q7576606}}\n\n[[Category:Biological pest control wasps]]\n[[Category:Crabronidae]]\n[[Category:Hymenoptera of North America]]\n[[Category:Insects described in 1823]]\n", "text_old": "{{Good article}}\n{{Speciesbox\n | image               = Western CKs mating.jpg \n | image_alt           = Two amber-yellow wasps, male above, female below, mate in some grass, tails touching.\n | image_caption       = Two ''Sphecius grandis'' wasps mate (male above, female below), in [[Big Bend (Texas)|Big Bend, Texas]].\n | taxon            = Sphecius grandis\n | authority  = ([[Thomas Say|Say]], 1823)<ref>{{cite journal | url=https://www.redalyc.org/pdf/575/57523304.pdf | title=Sphecidae y Crabronidae (Hymenoptera) \u2013 De algunos Municipios del Centro y Sur de Tamaulipas, M\u00e9xico | author=V\u00edctor, Jorge | journal=Acta Zool\u00f3gica Mexicana | year=2007 | volume=23 | issue=3 | pages=35\u201348 | url-status=live | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925021139/http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/pdf/575/57523304.pdf | archive-date=2012-09-25 | df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://essigdb.berkeley.edu/cgi/eme_query?bnhm_id=EMEC55413&one=T&OK2SHOWPRIVATE=1 | title=Detail of Catalog ID# EMEC55413 | publisher=Essig Museum of Entomology | date=December 6, 2004 | accessdate=August 15, 2011 | author=Nishida, Gordon}}</ref>\n | synonyms            = ''Stizus grandis'' <small>Say, 1823</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Sphecius grandis''''', also called the '''western cicada killer''', is a species of [[Sphecius|cicada killer wasp]] (''Sphecius''). The western species shares the same [[Nest|nesting biology]] as its fellow species, the eastern cicada killer (''[[Sphecius speciosus|S. speciosus]]''). ''S.&nbsp;grandis'', like all other species of the [[genus]] ''Sphecius'', mainly provides [[cicada]]s for its offspring. It forms nest aggregations and mates and [[Voltinism|broods once in a year]], in July and early August. The wasp is on average {{convert|3|cm|in|round=0.5|abbr=on}} to {{convert|5|cm|in|round=0.5|abbr=on}} in length and is amber-yellow with yellow rings on its [[abdomen]].\n\nWasps in the genus ''Sphecius'' are not habitually aggressive and use their [[venom]] mainly to paralyse cicadas which they take back to their nests to feed their young. The females catch around four or more cicadas for provisioning, place them in brood cells and lay eggs in the cells. ''S.&nbsp;grandis'' is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Central America]], Mexico and the [[Western United States]], and is found at a higher mean altitude than other species of ''Sphecius''. The western cicada killer males emerge earlier than females, but generally die after only a couple of days.\n\n''Sphecius grandis'' can be distinguished from ''S.&nbsp;convallis'' (the Pacific cicada killer wasp) by the coloration pattern of the gastral [[Tergum|tergites]]. Formerly, the two species were distinguished on the basis of the number of tergites with yellow markings (five in ''S.&nbsp;grandis'' and three in ''S.&nbsp;convallis''), but a more recent study showed that this character was insufficient to distinguish the two species. However, they can be distinguished by the density of the punctation on the first and second tergites.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe western cicada killer was first described by American naturalist [[Thomas Say]] in 1824 in [[Madera Canyon]], Arizona, as ''Stizus grandis''. Its species name is the [[Latin]] adjective ''grandis'' meaning \"large\". It is one of five species of the genus ''[[Sphecius]]'' in North America.<ref name=\"bionica\">{{cite journal | url=http://www.bio-nica.info/biblioteca/Holliday2006Sphecius.pdf | title=Improved Key to New World Species of Sphecius (Hymenoptera: Crabronidae |author1=Holliday, Charles W. |author2=Coelho, Joseph R. | journal=Annals of the Entomological Society of America | year=2006 | volume=99 | pages=793\u2013798 | doi=10.1603/0013-8746(2006)99[793:IKTNWS]2.0.CO;2 | issue=5}}</ref>\n\nMore recently, it has been suspected that the western cicada killer represents more than one species. It co-occurs with the eastern cicada killer (''S.&nbsp;speciosus'') and Pacific cicada killer (''S.&nbsp;convallis'') at [[Big Bend National Park]] in Texas. There the three wasps hunt and nest in the same locales, and the eastern and western cicada killers hunt the same cicada species. Analysis of [[mitochondrial DNA]] showed that the western cicada killer contains two divergent [[clade]]s, which may represent distinct species. The two clades appeared to be split by the [[Rocky Mountains]], with one occurring mainly to the south and east, the other to the west.<ref name=\"zoot\">{{cite journal|author1=Hastings, Jon M. |author2=Schultheis, Patrick J. |author3=Whitson, Maggie |author4=Holliday, Charles W. |author5=Coelho, Joseph R. |author6=Mendell, Angela M. |year=2008|title=DNA barcoding of new world cicada killers (Hymenoptera: Crabronidae)|journal=[[Zootaxa]]|volume=1713|pages=27\u201338|url=http://www.mapress.com/zootaxa/2008/f/zt01713p038.pdf|hdl=10385/598}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nRanging in size from {{convert|3|to|5|cm|in|round=0.5|abbr=on}} in length, the western cicada killer is very similar to its eastern cousin, ''[[Sphecius speciosus]]'', with a [[rufous]] black hue to the body, amber stripes and a yellow abdomen.<ref name=\"bionica\" /><ref>{{cite journal| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RsVLAAAAYAAJ&q=sphecius+grandis&dq=sphecius+grandis | title=Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia | journal=American Natural History | year=1901 | volume=53 | pages=788\u2013794 | author1=Philadelphia | first1=Academy of Natural Sciences of}}</ref><ref name=\"cdri\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cdri.org/fieldguides/wasps/taxonomy/robust-yellow-group.html | title=Wasps (Order: Hymenoptera) \u2013 Robust Yellow Group | publisher=[[Chihuahuan Desert Nature Center and Botanical Gardens]] | access-date=August 11, 2011 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927062046/http://www.cdri.org/fieldguides/wasps/taxonomy/robust-yellow-group.html | archive-date=September 27, 2011 | df= }}</ref> The western cicada killer has rufous spots on its first to second tergites and yellow markings can generally be found from first to fifth, although there is some variation.<ref name=\"bionica\" /> On average, female [[forewing]] length lies between {{convert|2.5|and|3|cm|in|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"jstor\" /> Females are larger than males and live for a year, a time just long enough to produce a brood, whereas the males die in only a few days, just enough time to impregnate a female.<ref name=\"cdri\" /> In Steven J. Phillips' book ''A Natural History of the Sonoran Desert'', he referred to them as superficially resembling \"huge yellowjackets or hornets\" and stated that they are \"powerful fliers with compound eyes\".<ref>[[#Phillips|Phillips (1999)]], p. 346</ref> On average, males weigh 95{{nbsp;}}[[Milligram|mg]] and females are far heavier, at 256{{nbsp;}}mg,<ref>[[#Vander Wall|Vander Wall (1990)]], p. 38</ref> probably because of the additional weight of the ovaries, developing eggs and nutritional reserves. Nevertheless, the ratio between flight muscle mass and body mass is the same for both sexes.<ref name=\"jspss\">{{cite journal| title=Sexual size dimorphism and flight behavior in cicada killers | author=Coelho, Joseph R. | journal=Oikos |date=June 1997 | volume=79 | issue=2 | pages=371\u2013375 | doi=10.2307/3546021 | jstor=3546021}}</ref>\n\n===Identification===\nDistinguishing ''S.&nbsp;grandis'' from the other four New World species of ''[[Sphecius]]'' (''[[Sphecius convallis|S.&nbsp;convallis]]'', ''[[Sphecius hogardii|S.&nbsp;hogardii]]'', ''[[Sphecius speciosus|S. speciosus]]'', ''[[Sphecius spectabilis|S.&nbsp;spectabilis]]'') is difficult. The female ''S.&nbsp;convallis'' was originally distinguished from the female ''S. grandis'' by the yellow marks from the first to third gastral [[Tergum|tergites]] on ''S.&nbsp;convallis'' and yellow marks on all tergites for ''S.&nbsp;grandis''. However, this was found to be insufficient for correct identification because the positions of the markings can vary among different wasps of the same species.<ref name=\"bionica\" />\n\nCharles W. Holliday and Joseph R. Coelho devised a new key in 2004 to identify the ''Sphecius'' species, examining 4,451 wasps among the five New World species, and noting that 98% of the female ''S. convallis'' wasps examined had yellow markings on gastral tergites one to four (or fewer) and ''S.&nbsp;grandis'' had 98% yellow markings from tergites one to five (or more). The 2% percent of ''S.&nbsp;grandis'' that overlapped with ''S.&nbsp;convallis'' were determined by density of the punctation in colour of the first tergum against the second. The markings on ''S.&nbsp;grandis'' males were found to be the same as on females.<ref name=\"bionica\" />\n\n===Thermoregulation===\nIt has been found that the western cicada killer wasp is capable of [[thermoregulation]] which enables them to maintain territories during the day.<ref name=\"sasi\" /> A study by Joseph R. Coelho showed that during territorial patrolling the species had a high and regulated [[Thorax (insect anatomy)|thorax]] temperature. Experiments found that the wasp has the ability to shift heat from its thorax to its abdomen and that the abdomen is generally kept colder than the thorax. Dead wasps that were placed in the sun reached abnormally high temperatures when compared to those on nearby plants.<ref name=\"scdir\">{{cite journal | title=Thermoregulation in male western cicada killers (''Sphecius grandis'' Say) in the Chihuahuan desert |author1=Coelho, Joseph R. |author2=Holliday, Charles W. |author3=Hastings, Jon. M. |author4=Maty, Elizabeth |author5=Swigart, Meghan |author6=Mendel, Angela | journal=Journal of Thermal Biology |date=July 2007 | volume=32 | issue=5 | pages=270\u2013275 | doi = 10.1016/j.jtherbio.2007.01.016 }}</ref>\n\n==Life cycle==\n\n===Emergence and mating===\nAfter [[Egg (biology)|hatching]], the offspring feed on the tissue of the cicadas provided by their mother. Males emerge before females and both genders are [[Sexual maturity|sexually receptive]] from emergence in July to early August, when they mate and brood. English naturalist [[Charles Darwin]] postulated that the pattern of male emergence before females evolved by [[natural selection]] to improve the chances of the male mating. The timing of the emergence of females has evolved to correspond with the similar emergence of the cicada species of the area, ''[[Tibicen|Tibicen duryi]]'' and ''T.&nbsp;parallela'', which they hunt for the provisioning of their nests.<ref name=\"jstor2\">{{cite journal |jstor=4600338 | title=Protandry in western cicada killer wasps (''Sphecius grandis'', Hymnoptera: Sphecidae) and empirical study of emergence time and mating opportunity | author=Hastings, Jon | journal=Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology |date=April 1989 | volume=25 | issue=4 | pages=255\u2013260 |doi=10.1007/BF00300051}}</ref> Many have yellow markings located on their [[Tergum|tergites]] ([[Anatomical terms of location#Dorsal and ventral|dorsal portion]]), although some have been found only from the first to fifth tergites.<ref name=\"bionica\"/>\n\n[[File:Cicada Killer Wasp.jpg|thumb|''[[Sphecius speciosus]]'' (eastern cicada killer) shares many behavioral similarities with ''Sphecius grandis''.]]\nBecause males emerge earlier than females, the males compete for mating territories surrounding the nests in which the females are located. During a fight, the males risk damaging their wings or appendages by butting and grappling.<ref name=\"sandwas2\">[[#Evans|Evans (2007)]], p. 35</ref> Another defense technique is to grab another male and carry it high into the air, which is thought to be a demonstration of strength. As a general rule, the larger the male the more predominant he is in battles.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Hastings, Jon |year=1990 |title=Sexual-size dimorphism in Western cicada killer wasps, ''Sphecius grandis'' (Hymenoptera: Sphecidae) |journal=Transactions of the Kentucky Academy of Science |volume=50 |issue=1\u20132 |pages=1\u20135 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/104927#page/261/mode/1up}}</ref> Age influences the success in the defense and security of territory; the younger the wasp the greater the chance of a successful takeover of territory. Some small males even engage in non-territorial mating tactics,<ref name=\"jsps2\">{{cite journal | title=The Influence of Size, Age and Residency Status in Territory Defense in Male Western Cicada Killer Wasps (''Sphecius grandis'', Hymenoptera: Sphecidae) | author=Hastings, Jon M. | journal=Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society |date=July 1989 | volume=62 | issue=3 | pages=363\u2013373 | jstor=25085103}}</ref> and delay their emergence so as to have a fairer chance of survival.<ref name=\"ox\">{{cite journal | url=http://beheco.oxfordjournals.org/content/13/3/337.full | title=Protandry models and their application to salmon | author=Morbey, Yoland E. | journal=Behavioral Ecology |date=June 2001 | volume=13 | issue=3 | pages=337\u2013343 | doi=10.1093/beheco/13.3.337| citeseerx=10.1.1.555.6866 }}</ref>\n\nOn emergence from the nest, the female is sexually receptive but does not choose her mate, but instead [[copulation (zoology)|copulates]] with the first male of her species that finds her.<ref name=\"jstor2\" /> Once the female has mated, she rebuffs all advances by other wasps.\n\n===Nesting and perching===\nMales perch after emerging from their nest. They pick out an area close to a nest with females inside and guard the territory around it so as to have a better chance of mating. They tend to perch on many different [[Substrate (biology)|substrates]] such as stumps, pebbles, wood, weeds, grass blades and low tree branches. Males assume an alert posture, ready for a challenge from another male, or from a predator. One study by a [[Behavioral ecology|behavioral ecologist]], [[John Alcock (behavioral ecologist)|John Alcock]], showed that a large majority of the marked wasps returned to the same perch day after day, and two males swapped between two different sites.<ref name=\"tand\">{{cite journal | title=The behaviour of western cicada killer males, ''Sphecius grandis'' (Sphecidae, Hymenoptera) | author=Alcock, John | journal=[[Journal of Natural History]] | year=1975 | volume=9 | issue=5 | pages=561\u2013566 |doi=10.1080/00222937500770431}}</ref> The species rarely perches on the ground.<ref name=\"scdir\" />\n\nIt shares the same [[Nest|nesting biology]] as ''S.&nbsp;speciosus''.<ref name=\"jstor\">{{cite journal |jstor=25084766 | title=Provisioning by female Western cicada killer wasps, ''Sphecius grandis'' (Hymnoptera: Sphecidae): influence of body size and emergence time on individual provisioning success | author=Hastings, Jon | journal=[[Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society]] |date=April 1986 | volume=59 | issue=2 | pages=262\u2013268}}</ref> All [[Sphecius|cicada killers]] are ground-nesting insects and nest aggregations can contain up to hundreds of nests, each with a single provisioning female.<ref name=\"zoot\" /> Their tunnel is mainly made in well-drained, bare sandy soil,<ref name=\"kentu\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ca.uky.edu/entomology/entfacts/ef004.asp | title=Cicada Killer Wasps | publisher=[[University of Kentucky]] | year=2010 | accessdate=August 23, 2011 | author=Townsend, Lee}}</ref> frequently under sidewalks,<ref name=\"natu\" /> but is generally in full sunlight. Approximately 90% of its life is spent underground as a larva.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://sites.lafayette.edu/hollidac/research/biology-of-cicada-killer-wasps/ | title=Biology of cicada killer wasps | publisher=[[Lafayette College]] | date=November 16, 2009 | accessdate=August 15, 2011 | author=Kosmeier, Dieter}}</ref> It rarely infests grounds that are rich in vegetation in order for them to get more sun. Mounds are easily recognizable by their distinctive U-shaped digging entrance.<ref name=\"kentu\" />\n\n===Feeding and hunting habits===\n''Sphecius grandis'' has very similar nesting and feeding habits to other members of its genus, most notably ''Sphecius speciosus''.<ref name=\"jstor\" /><ref name=\"jstor2\" /> As with ''S.&nbsp;speciosus'',<ref>{{cite web | url=http://entomology.ifas.ufl.edu/creatures/beneficial/cicada_killers.htm | title=Cicada killers | publisher=[[Florida Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services]] | date=June 2003 | accessdate=August 11, 2011 | author=Stange, Lionel A.}}</ref> the female hunts for [[cicada]]s in low tree trunks, helped by the calls of the cicada males, and paralyses the insect by piercing the [[central nervous system]] with her [[stinger]].<ref name=\"kentu\" /><ref name=\"natu\">{{cite journal | url=http://www.nature.nps.gov/views/KCs/SonoranDesert/Media/Documents/JUNTOS_EnglishPDFs/Juntosengunit2.pdf | title=A Dynamic Balance Living in the Sonoran Desert | author=Zolinas, Zachary | journal=Juntos, Unit Two | year=1999 | pages=12}}</ref> She drags the cicadas back to her nest to place them in brood cells in which she eventually lays one egg per cell.<ref name=\"jstor\" /> Females carry cicadas that are on average 88% heavier than their own body mass. It has been hypothesised that cicada killers may also have the ability to capture cicadas mid-flight.<ref name=\"jspss\" /> There are approximately two or more cicadas to each brood cell.<ref name=\"jstor\" /><ref name=\"kentu\" /> When the larvae hatch, the cicada provides nutrition for the offspring to feed on.<ref name=\"jstor\" />\n\nThe wasps preferentially hunt for female cicadas because they have more consumable tissue, but male cicadas are easier to locate, which explains the systemic bias towards male kills.<ref name=\"bioo\">{{cite journal |author1=Holliday, Charles W. |author2=Hastings, Jon M. |author3=Coelho, Joseph R. |year=2009 |title=Cicada prey of New World cicada killers, ''Sphecius'' spp. (Dahlbom, 1843) (Hymenoptera: Crabronidae) |journal=Entomological News |volume=120 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201317 |doi=10.3157/021.120.0101}}</ref> They chiefly hunt for ''[[Tibicen duryi]]'', ''[[Tibicen dealbata]]'' and ''[[Tibicen parallela]]''.<ref>{{cite journal | url=http://www.fcla.edu/FlaEnt/fe91p657.pdf | title=Body Size Relationship Between Sphecius speciosus (Hymenoptera: Crabronidae) and their Prey: Prey Size Determines Wasp Size |author1=Coelho, Joseph R. |author2=Holliday, Charles W. |author3=Hastings, Jon M. | journal=Florida Entomologist |date=December 2008 | volume=91 | issue=4 | pages=657\u2013663 | doi=10.1653/0015-4040-91.4.657 }}</ref><ref name=\"sandwas\" /> Cicada killers are capable of [[thermoregulation]], which allows them to hunt for cicadas during the day, when the cicadas are most prominent.<ref name=\"sasi\">{{cite conference | url=http://www.sasionline.org/instar/Instar42.pdf | title=The 17th Annual IECC Conference | publisher=[[Sonoran Arthropod Studies Institute|SASI]] | accessdate=August 15, 2011 | author=Olson, Carl A.| booktitle=SASI's Communication Quarterly | year=2009 | conference=The 17th Annual IECC Conference | pages=8}}</ref> The species is mostly harmless to humans.<ref name=\"natu\" /> Some males when emerging early fly into the trees to feed on [[sap]],<ref name=\"tand\" /> and the species has been known to feed on [[nectar]].<ref name=\"kentu\" /><ref name=\"bios\">{{cite journal | url=http://biostor.org/reference/80292 | title=Territoriality and mating behavior of ''Sphex pensylvanicus'' L. (Hymenoptera: Sphecidae) | author=Kurczewski, F. E. | journal=Journal of Hymenoptera Research | year=1998 | volume=7 | issue=1 | pages=74\u201383}}</ref>\n\nStings of this species received a lethality rating of 46&nbsp;LC measured by LC={{frac|\u03bcg|LD<sub>50</sub>}} (LC=\"lethal capacity\", \u03bcg=\"venom in the insect\", LD<sub>50</sub>=\"{{frac|\u03bcg|g}} of the venom\", g=\"size of mammal receiving the dose\" and LD=\"lethal dose\").<ref>[[#Resh|Resh (2009)]], p. 1030</ref><ref name=\"scfa\" />\n\n==Geographical distribution==\nWestern cicada killers are found at a higher altitude than most other ''Sphecius'' species and are [[sympatry|sympatric]] with the species ''S.&nbsp;convallis'' and ''S.&nbsp;speciosus'', even though ''S.&nbsp;grandis'' are on average found at higher altitudes than ''S.&nbsp;convallis''. A study showed that the mean elevation for ''S.&nbsp;grandis'' was 755&nbsp;[[metre|m]] \u00b1 23.3&nbsp;m, compared with the lower results of ''S.&nbsp;speciosus'' (219&nbsp;m \u00b1 4.7&nbsp;m), ''S.&nbsp;convallis'' (582&nbsp;m \u00b1 30.9&nbsp;m) and ''S.&nbsp;hogardii'' (18&nbsp;m \u00b1 5&nbsp;m).<ref name=\"benth\">{{cite journal | url=http://www.benthamscience.com/open/toentoj/articles/V005/31TOENTOJ.pdf | title=The Geographic Distributions of Cicada Killers (''Sphecius''; Hymenoptera, Crabronidae) in the America | author1=Coelho, Joseph R. | author2=Holliday, Charles W. | author3=Hastings, Jon M. | journal=The Open Entomology Journal | date=March 2011 | volume=5 | pages=31\u201338 | doi=10.2174/1874407901105010031 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401201002/http://www.benthamscience.com/open/toentoj/articles/V005/31TOENTOJ.pdf | archive-date=2012-04-01 | df= }}</ref> The species is [[Nearctic ecozone|Nearctic]] and [[Neotropic ecozone|Neotropic]], found from [[Central America]] to the [[Western United States]],<ref name=\"sandwas\">[[#Evans|Evans (2007)]], p. 34</ref> in [[New Mexico]], [[California]] and every state west of the [[Rocky Mountains]], except [[Wyoming]], as well as [[Kansas]], [[Oklahoma]] and [[Nebraska]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://aces.nmsu.edu/academics/arthropods/spotlight-specimens-in-t.html | title=Spotlight Specimens in the Museum | publisher=[[New Mexico State University]] | year=2008 | access-date=August 23, 2011 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007015948/http://aces.nmsu.edu/academics/arthropods/spotlight-specimens-in-t.html | archive-date=October 7, 2011 | df= }}</ref><ref name=\"hydr\" /> ''S.&nbsp;grandis'' is most commonly found in [[riparian zones]]. It has been observed in such places in Mexico as [[Baja California Norte]], [[Baja California Sur]], [[Coahuila]], [[Nuevo Leon]], [[Tamaulipas]] and [[Yucat\u00e1n (state)|Yucat\u00e1n]] and also in [[Granada, Nicaragua|Granada]] ([[Nicaragua]]), [[Guanacaste Province|Guanacaste]] ([[Costa Rica]]) and [[Honduras]].<ref name=\"benth\" />\n\n==Interaction with humans==\n''Sphecius grandis'' wasps frequently interact with humans because of their tendency to make their nests in backyards, gardens and sidewalks.<ref name=\"natu\" /> Pest control is mostly unneeded as they nest in areas with little to no vegetation, usually ignore people, and females are not aggressive, tending to save their venom for their cicada prey,<ref name=\"cdri\" /> but will sting if they are grabbed or stepped on.<ref name=\"kentu\" /><ref name=\"hydr\" /><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.masterbeekeeper.org/stinging/cicadakiller.htm | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050306001320/http://www.masterbeekeeper.org/stinging/cicadakiller.htm | url-status=dead | archive-date=2005-03-06 | title=Stinging Insects: Cicada Killer Wasps | publisher=Masterbeekeeper.org | work=Dyce Laboratory for Honey Bee Studies | date=July 2004 | access-date=August 23, 2011 | author=Gardner, Kathryn }}</ref> Despite their large size, being the largest wasp to inhabit California,<ref name=\"hydr\">{{cite web | url=http://www.hydrex.info/cicada-killer-wasp/ | title=Cicada Killer Wasp | publisher=Hydrex Pest Control | accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> their sting has been reported as being between merely numbing and sharp to moderate.<ref name=\"scfa\">{{cite journal | url=https://www.scfaz.com/content/downloadable_materials/dealing_wBugs1.pdf | title=Pain Ratings of Solitary Wasps | author=Conniff, Richard | journal=Prescription Treatment Quarterly | date=April 2002 | volume=21 | issue=1 | pages=1\u201318 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320005139/https://www.scfaz.com/content/downloadable_materials/dealing_wBugs1.pdf | archive-date=2012-03-20 | df= }}</ref><ref name=\"cals\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cals.uidaho.edu/edComm/pdf/BUL/BUL0853.pdf | title=Homeowner Guide to Minor Stinging Insects | publisher=[[University of Idaho]] | date=May 2009 | accessdate=August 17, 2011 | pages=1\u20138}}</ref> Males, while smaller, are naturally more aggressive and less tolerant of disturbance.<ref name=\"kentu\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|32em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book | title=The Sand Wasps: Natural History and Behavior | url=https://archive.org/details/sandwaspsnatural0000evan | url-access=registration | publisher=[[Harvard University Press]] | author=Evans, Ensign Howard |author2=Kevin M. O'Neill |year=2007 | isbn=978-0-674-02462-5 |ref=Evans}}\n* {{cite book | title=Encyclopedia of Insects | publisher=[[Elsevier]] | author=Resh, Vincent H. | author2=Card\u00e9, Ring T. | year=2009 | isbn=978-0-12-586990-4 | ref=Resh | url-access=registration | url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofin00bada }}\n* {{cite book | title=A Natural History of the Sonoran Desert | author=Phillips, Steven J. | author2=Comus, Patricia Wentworth | year=1999 | isbn=978-0-520-21980-9 | publisher=[[Arizona-Sonora Desert Museum]] | ref=Phillips | url-access=registration | url=https://archive.org/details/naturalhistoryof00ariz }}\n* {{cite book | title=Food hoarding in animals | url=https://archive.org/details/foodhoardinginan0000vand | url-access=registration |author1=Vander Wall |author2=Stephen B. | year=1990 |isbn=978-0-226-84735-1 |publisher =[[University of Chicago Press]] | ref=Vander Wall}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Sphecius grandis}}\n{{Portal|Insects}}\n* ''[http://www.discoverlife.org/mp/20q?search=Sphecius+grandis Sphecius grandis]'' at Discover Life\n* ''[http://zipcodezoo.com/Animals/S/Sphecius_grandis/ Sphecius grandis]'' at ZipcodeZoo\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q7576606}}\n\n[[Category:Biological pest control wasps]]\n[[Category:Crabronidae]]\n[[Category:Hymenoptera of North America]]\n[[Category:Insects described in 1823]]\n", "name_user": "An Errant Knight", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sphecius_grandis"}
{"title_page": "Holotomography", "text_new": "'''Holotomography''' (HT) is a laser technique to measure three-dimensional [[refractive index]] (RI) tomogram of a microscopic sample such as biological cells and tissues. Because the RI can serve as an intrinsic imaging contrast for transparent or phase objects, measurements of RI tomograms can provide label-free quantitative imaging of microscopic phase objects. In order to measure 3-D RI tomogram of samples, HT employs the principle of holographic imaging and inverse scattering. Typically, multiple 2D holographic images of a sample are measured at various illumination angles, employing the principle of interferometric imaging. Then, a 3D RI tomogram of the sample is reconstructed from these multiple 2D holographic images by inversely solving light scattering in the sample.\n\nThe principle of HT is very similar to X-ray computed tomography (CT) or [[CT scan]]. CT scan measures multiple 2-D X-ray images of a human body at various illumination angles, and a 3-D tomogram (X-ray absorptivity) is then retrieved via the inverse scattering theory. Both the X-ray CT and laser HT shares the same governing equation \u2013 [[Helmholtz equation]],  [[Wave equation|the wave equatio]]<nowiki/>n for a monochromatic wavelength. HT is also known as optical diffraction tomography.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lauer|first=V|date=2002|title=New approach to optical diffraction tomography yielding a vector equation of diffraction tomography and a novel tomographic microscope|journal=Journal of Microscopy|volume=205|issue=2|pages=165\u2013176|doi=10.1046/j.0022-2720.2001.00980.x|pmid=11879431}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe first theoretical proposal was presented by Emil Wolf,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wolf|first=Emil|date=1969|title=Three-dimensional structure determination of semi-transparent objects from holographic data|url=|journal=Optics Communications|volume=1|issue=4|pages=153\u2013156|bibcode=1969OptCo...1..153W|doi=10.1016/0030-4018(69)90052-2}}</ref> and the first experimental demonstration was shown by Fercher et al.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fercher|first=A.F.|last2=Bartelt|first2=H.|last3=Becker|first3=H.|last4=Wiltschko|first4=E.|date=1979|title=Image formation by inversion of scattered field data: experiments and computational simulation|journal=Applied Optics|volume=18|issue=14|pages=2427\u201339|bibcode=1979ApOpt..18.2427F|doi=10.1364/AO.18.002427|pmid=20212679}}</ref> From 2000s, HT techniques had been extensively studied and applied to the field of biology and medicine, by several research groups including the MIT spectroscopy laboratory. Both the technical developments and applications of HT have been significantly advanced. During the mid 2010s, first commercial HT companies Nanolive and Tomocube were founded.\n\n== Applications ==\nThe applications of HT includes    \n[[File:3D RI image of a live cell.gif|thumb|3D RI tomogram of a live cell (macrophage)]]\n\n=== Cell biology ===\nHT provides 3D dynamic images of live cells and thin tissues without using exogenous labeling agents such as fluorescence proteins or dyes. HT enables quantitative live cell imaging, and also provides quantitative information such as cell volume, surface area, protein concentration. HT provides following advantages over conventional 3D microscopic techniques.  \n# Label-free: Cellular membrane and subcellular organelles can clearly be imaged without using exogenous labeling agents. Thus, there are no issues of phototoxicity, photobleaching, and photodamaging.\n# Quantitative imaging capability: HT directly measures cell\u2019s 3D RI maps, which is intrinsic optical properties of materials. Because the measured RI can be translated into the mass density of a cell and using this information, mass of a cell can also be retrieved.\n# Precise and fast measurements: HT provides the spatial resolution down to approximately 100&nbsp;nm and the temporal resolution of a few to a hundred frames per second, depending on the numerical apertures of used objective lenses and the speed of an image sensor.\nHowever, 3D RI tomography does not provide molecular specificity. Generally, the measured RI information cannot be directly related to information about molecules or proteins, except for notable cases such as gold nanoparties<ref>{{cite biorxiv|last=Kim|first=Doyeon|date=2016|title=Label-free high-resolution 3-D imaging of gold nanoparticles inside live cells using optical diffraction tomography|biorxiv=10.1101/097113}}</ref> or lipid droplets<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Kyoohyun|date=2016|title=Three-dimensional label-free imaging and quantification of lipid droplets in live hepatocytes|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=6|pages=36815|bibcode=2016NatSR...636815K|arxiv=1611.01774|doi=10.1038/srep36815|pmid=27874018|pmc=5118789}}</ref> that exhibit distinctly high RI values compared to cell cytoplams.\n\n=== Correlative imaging ===\nHT can be used with other imaging modalities for correlative imaging. For example, a combination of HT and fluorescence imaging enables a synergistic analytic approach.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Live Cell Imaging with Holotomography and Fluorescence|journal=Microscopy Today|volume=28|pages=18\u201323|doi=10.1017/S1551929519001032|year=2020|last1=Lambert|first1=Aubrey|doi-access=free}}</ref> HT provides structural information whereas fluorescence signal provides molecular specific imaging, an optical analogous to PET/CT. Various approaches have been reported for correlative imaging approaches using HT.\n\n=== Lipid quantification ===\nIntracellular lipid droplets play important roles in energy storage and metabolism, and are also related to various pathologies, including cancer, obesity, and diabetes mellitus. HT enables label-free and quantitative imaging and analysis for free or intracellular lipid droplets. Because lipid droplets have distinctly high RI (''n'' > 1.375) compared to other parts of cytoplasm, the measurements of RI tomograms provide information about the volume, concentration, and dry mass of lipid droplets.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Three-dimensional label-free imaging and quantification of lipid droplets in live hepatocytes|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=6|pages=36815|doi=10.1038/srep36815|year=2016|last1=Kim|first1=Kyoohyun|last2=Lee|first2=Seoeun|last3=Yoon|first3=Jonghee|last4=Heo|first4=Jihan|last5=Choi|first5=Chulhee|last6=Park|first6=Yongkeun|bibcode=2016NatSR...636815K|arxiv=1611.01774}}</ref> Recently, HT was used to evaluate the therapeutic effects of a nanodrug designed to affect the targeted delivery of lobeglitazone by measuring lipid droplets in foam cells.\n\n=== Experimental Laboratory ===\nHT provide various quantitative imaging capability, providing morphological, biochemical, and mechanical properties of individuals cells. 3D RI tomography directly provides morphological properties including volume, surface area, and [[sphericity]] (roundness) of a cell. Local RI value can be translated into biochemical information or cytoplasmic protein concentration, because the RI of a solution is linearly proportional to its concentration.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Baber|first=R.|date=1952|title=Interference microscopy and mass determination|journal=Nature|volume=169|issue=4296|pages=366\u20137|pmid=14919571|doi=10.1038/169366b0|bibcode=1952Natur.169..366B}}</ref> In particular, for the case of [[red blood cell]]s, RI value can be converted into hemoglobin concentration. Measurements of dynamic cell membrane fluctuation, which can also be obtained with a HT instrument, provides information about cellular deformability. Furthermore, these various quantitative parameters can be obtained at the single cell level, allowing correlative analysis between various cellular parameters. HT has been utilized for the study of red blood cells, white blood cells,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yoon|first=Jonghee|date=2015|title=Label-free characterization of white blood cells by measuring 3D refractive index maps|journal=Biomedical Optics Express|volume=6|issue=10|pages=3865\u201375|pmid=26504637|pmc=4605046|doi=10.1364/BOE.6.003865|bibcode=2015arXiv150502609Y|arxiv=1505.02609}}</ref> malaria infection.\n\n== See also ==\n* quantitative phase imaging\n* [[digital holographic microscopy]]\n* [[holography]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Imaging]]\n[[Category:Scientific instruments]]\n", "text_old": "'''Holotomography''' (HT) is a laser technique to measure three-dimensional [[refractive index]] (RI) tomogram of a microscopic sample such as biological cells and tissues. Because the RI can serve as an intrinsic imaging contrast for transparent or phase objects, measurements of RI tomograms can provide label-free quantitative imaging of microscopic phase objects. In order to measure 3-D RI tomogram of samples, HT employs the principle of holographic imaging and inverse scattering. Typically, multiple 2D holographic images of a sample are measured at various illumination angles, employing the principle of interferometric imaging. Then, a 3D RI tomogram of the sample is reconstructed from these multiple 2D holographic images by inversely solving light scattering in the sample.\n\nThe principle of HT is very similar to X-ray computed tomography (CT) or [[CT scan]]. CT scan measures multiple 2-D X-ray images of a human body at various illumination angles, and a 3-D tomogram (X-ray absorptivity) is then retrieved via the inverse scattering theory. Both the X-ray CT and laser HT shares the same governing equation \u2013 [[Helmholtz equation]],  [[Wave equation|the wave equatio]]<nowiki/>n for a monochromatic wavelength. HT is also known as optical diffraction tomography.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lauer|first=V|date=2002|title=New approach to optical diffraction tomography yielding a vector equation of diffraction tomography and a novel tomographic microscope|journal=Journal of Microscopy|volume=205|issue=2|pages=165\u2013176|doi=10.1046/j.0022-2720.2001.00980.x|pmid=11879431}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe first theoretical proposal was presented by Emil Wolf,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wolf|first=Emil|date=1969|title=Three-dimensional structure determination of semi-transparent objects from holographic data|url=|journal=Optics Communications|volume=1|issue=4|pages=153\u2013156|bibcode=1969OptCo...1..153W|doi=10.1016/0030-4018(69)90052-2}}</ref> and the first experimental demonstration was shown by Fercher et al.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fercher|first=A.F.|last2=Bartelt|first2=H.|last3=Becker|first3=H.|last4=Wiltschko|first4=E.|date=1979|title=Image formation by inversion of scattered field data: experiments and computational simulation|journal=Applied Optics|volume=18|issue=14|pages=2427\u201339|bibcode=1979ApOpt..18.2427F|doi=10.1364/AO.18.002427|pmid=20212679}}</ref> From 2000s, HT techniques had been extensively studied and applied to the field of biology and medicine, by several research groups including the MIT spectroscopy laboratory. Both the technical developments and applications of HT have been significantly advanced. During the mid 2010s, first commercial HT companies Nanolive and Tomocube were founded.\n\n== Applications ==\nThe applications of HT includes<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Park|first=YongKeun|date=2018|title=Quantitative phase imaging in biomedicine|journal=Nature Photonics|volume=12|issue=10|pages=578\u2013589|doi=10.1038/s41566-018-0253-x|bibcode=2018NaPho..12..578P}}</ref>    \n[[File:3D RI image of a live cell.gif|thumb|3D RI tomogram of a live cell (macrophage)]]\n\n=== Cell biology ===\nHT provides 3D dynamic images of live cells and thin tissues without using exogenous labeling agents such as fluorescence proteins or dyes. HT enables quantitative live cell imaging, and also provides quantitative information such as cell volume, surface area, protein concentration. HT provides following advantages over conventional 3D microscopic techniques.  \n# Label-free: Cellular membrane and subcellular organelles can clearly be imaged without using exogenous labeling agents. Thus, there are no issues of phototoxicity, photobleaching, and photodamaging.\n# Quantitative imaging capability: HT directly measures cell\u2019s 3D RI maps, which is intrinsic optical properties of materials. Because the measured RI can be translated into the mass density of a cell and using this information, mass of a cell can also be retrieved.\n# Precise and fast measurements: HT provides the spatial resolution down to approximately 100&nbsp;nm and the temporal resolution of a few to a hundred frames per second, depending on the numerical apertures of used objective lenses and the speed of an image sensor.\nHowever, 3D RI tomography does not provide molecular specificity. Generally, the measured RI information cannot be directly related to information about molecules or proteins, except for notable cases such as gold nanoparties<ref>{{cite biorxiv|last=Kim|first=Doyeon|date=2016|title=Label-free high-resolution 3-D imaging of gold nanoparticles inside live cells using optical diffraction tomography|biorxiv=10.1101/097113}}</ref> or lipid droplets<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Kyoohyun|date=2016|title=Three-dimensional label-free imaging and quantification of lipid droplets in live hepatocytes|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=6|pages=36815|bibcode=2016NatSR...636815K|arxiv=1611.01774|doi=10.1038/srep36815|pmid=27874018|pmc=5118789}}</ref> that exhibit distinctly high RI values compared to cell cytoplams.\n\n=== Correlative imaging ===\nHT can be used with other imaging modalities for correlative imaging. For example, a combination of HT and fluorescence imaging enables a synergistic analytic approach.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Combining Three-Dimensional Quantitative Phase Imaging and Fluorescence Microscopy for the Study of Cell Pathophysiology|journal=Yale J Biol Med|volume=91|issue=3|pages=267\u2013277|pmc=6153632|year=2018|last1=Kim|first1=Y. S.|last2=Lee|first2=S.|last3=Jung|first3=J.|last4=Shin|first4=S.|last5=Choi|first5=H. G.|last6=Cha|first6=G. H.|last7=Park|first7=W.|last8=Lee|first8=S.|last9=Park|first9=Y.|pmid=30258314}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Live Cell Imaging with Holotomography and Fluorescence|journal=Microscopy Today|volume=28|pages=18\u201323|doi=10.1017/S1551929519001032|year=2020|last1=Lambert|first1=Aubrey|doi-access=free}}</ref> HT provides structural information whereas fluorescence signal provides molecular specific imaging, an optical analogous to PET/CT. Various approaches have been reported for correlative imaging approaches using HT.\n\n=== Lipid quantification ===\nIntracellular lipid droplets play important roles in energy storage and metabolism, and are also related to various pathologies, including cancer, obesity, and diabetes mellitus. HT enables label-free and quantitative imaging and analysis for free or intracellular lipid droplets. Because lipid droplets have distinctly high RI (''n'' > 1.375) compared to other parts of cytoplasm, the measurements of RI tomograms provide information about the volume, concentration, and dry mass of lipid droplets.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Three-dimensional label-free imaging and quantification of lipid droplets in live hepatocytes|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=6|pages=36815|doi=10.1038/srep36815|year=2016|last1=Kim|first1=Kyoohyun|last2=Lee|first2=Seoeun|last3=Yoon|first3=Jonghee|last4=Heo|first4=Jihan|last5=Choi|first5=Chulhee|last6=Park|first6=Yongkeun|bibcode=2016NatSR...636815K|arxiv=1611.01774}}</ref> Recently, HT was used to evaluate the therapeutic effects of a nanodrug designed to affect the targeted delivery of lobeglitazone by measuring lipid droplets in foam cells.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Label-Free Tomographic Imaging of Lipid Droplets in Foam Cells for Machine-Learning-Assisted Therapeutic Evaluation of Targeted Nanodrugs|journal=ACS Nano|volume=|pages=|doi=10.1021/acsnano.9b07993|pmid=31909985|year=2020|last1=Park|first1=Sangwoo|last2=Ahn|first2=Jae Won|last3=Jo|first3=Youngju|last4=Kang|first4=Ha-Young|last5=Kim|first5=Hyun Jung|last6=Cheon|first6=Yeongmi|last7=Kim|first7=Jin Won|last8=Park|first8=Yongkeun|last9=Lee|first9=Seongsoo|last10=Park|first10=Kyeongsoon}}</ref>\n\n=== Experimental Laboratory ===\nHT provide various quantitative imaging capability, providing morphological, biochemical, and mechanical properties of individuals cells. 3D RI tomography directly provides morphological properties including volume, surface area, and [[sphericity]] (roundness) of a cell. Local RI value can be translated into biochemical information or cytoplasmic protein concentration, because the RI of a solution is linearly proportional to its concentration.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Baber|first=R.|date=1952|title=Interference microscopy and mass determination|journal=Nature|volume=169|issue=4296|pages=366\u20137|pmid=14919571|doi=10.1038/169366b0|bibcode=1952Natur.169..366B}}</ref> In particular, for the case of [[red blood cell]]s, RI value can be converted into hemoglobin concentration. Measurements of dynamic cell membrane fluctuation, which can also be obtained with a HT instrument, provides information about cellular deformability. Furthermore, these various quantitative parameters can be obtained at the single cell level, allowing correlative analysis between various cellular parameters. HT has been utilized for the study of red blood cells,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Park|first=YongKeun|date=2010|title=Measurement of red blood cell mechanics during morphological changes|journal=PNAS|volume=107|issue=15|pages=6731\u20136|doi=10.1073/pnas.0909533107|pmid=20351261|pmc=2872375|bibcode=2010PNAS..107.6731P}}</ref> white blood cells,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yoon|first=Jonghee|date=2015|title=Label-free characterization of white blood cells by measuring 3D refractive index maps|journal=Biomedical Optics Express|volume=6|issue=10|pages=3865\u201375|pmid=26504637|pmc=4605046|doi=10.1364/BOE.6.003865|bibcode=2015arXiv150502609Y|arxiv=1505.02609}}</ref> malaria infection,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Park|first=YongKeun|title=Refractive index maps and membrane dynamics of human red blood cells parasitized by Plasmodium falciparum|journal=PNAS|volume=105|issue=37|pages=13730\u201313735|doi=10.1073/pnas.0806100105|pmid=18772382|pmc=2529332|year=2008|bibcode=2008PNAS..10513730P}}</ref> bebasia infection,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=HyunJoo|first=Park|date=2015|title=Characterizations of individual mouse red blood cells parasitized by Babesia microti using 3-D holographic microscopy|journal=Scientific Reports |volume=5|pages=10827|doi=10.1038/srep10827|pmid=26039793|pmc=4650620|bibcode=2015NatSR...510827P|arxiv=1505.00832}}</ref> blood storage,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Park|first=Hyunjoo|date=2016|title=Measuring cell surface area and deformability of individual human red blood cells over blood storage using quantitative phase imaging|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=6|pages=34257|pmid=27698484|pmc=5048416|doi=10.1038/srep34257|bibcode=2016NatSR...634257P}}</ref> and diabetes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lee|first=SangYun|date=2017|title=Refractive index tomograms and dynamic membrane fluctuations of red blood cells from patients with diabetes mellitus|url=|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=7|issue=1|pages=1039|pmid=28432323|pmc=5430658|doi=10.1038/s41598-017-01036-4|bibcode=2017NatSR...7.1039L}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* quantitative phase imaging\n* [[digital holographic microscopy]]\n* [[holography]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Imaging]]\n[[Category:Scientific instruments]]\n", "name_user": "213.55.220.252", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eLipid quantification)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Holotomography"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tamil Nadu", "text_new": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Tamil Nadu, India}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tamil Nadu\n| image           = \n| width           = \n| caption         = \n| map1            = India Tamil Nadu COVID-19 map.svg\n| legend1         = Map of districts with confirmed cases (as of 20 April)\n{{legend|#a50f15|100+ confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#de2d26|50\u201399 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#fc9272|10\u201349 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#fee5d9|1\u20139 confirmed cases}}\n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]]\n| first_case      = [[Chennai]]\n| arrival_date    = 7 March 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=07|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n<!-- The confirmed, active, recovery and deaths cases are fetched from the Wikidata; Kindly don't delete the codes below.-->| confirmed_cases = {{stringsplit | txt={{wdib|ps=1|P1603|qual=P585|sep=\"--\"|df=dmy}} |sep=\"--\" |idx=-1}}\n| active_cases    = {{formatnum: {{#expr: {{formatnum: {{stringsplit | txt={{wdib|ps=1|P1603|sep=\"--\"|df=dmy}} |sep=\"--\" |idx=-1}}-{{stringsplit | txt={{wdib|ps=1|P8010|sep=\"--\"|df=dmy}} |sep=\"--\" |idx=-1}}-{{stringsplit | txt={{wdib|ps=1|P1120|sep=\"--\"|df=dmy}} |sep=\"--\" |idx=-1}} -3 |R}} }} }}{{refn|group=note|2 deaths cross notified to other states. 1 patient died after turning negative for infection.}}\n| recovery_cases  = {{stringsplit | txt={{wdib|ps=1|P8010|qual=P585|sep=\"--\"|df=dmy}} |sep=\"--\" |idx=-1}}\n| deaths          = {{stringsplit | txt={{wdib|ps=1|P1120|qual=P585|sep=\"--\"|df=dmy}} |sep=\"--\" |idx=-1}}\n| suspected_cases = \n| territories     = [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tamil Nadu#Cases by districts|36 districts]]\n| total_ili       = 5<ref name=\"SARI-10Apr\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=10 April 2020|title=Severe acute respiratory illness surveillance for coronavirus disease 2019, India, 2020|url=http://www.ijmr.org.in/temp/IndianJMedRes000-2175279_060232.pdf|journal=Indian Journal of Medical Research|volume=|page=5|via=}}</ref>\n| website         = {{url|https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/}}<br/>[https://nhmtn.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/095ad0a1c0254b058fa36b32d1ab1977 COVID-19 Public dashboard]\n| youtube         = \n}}\nThe first case of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] in the Indian state of [[Tamil Nadu]] was reported on 7 March 2020. The [[Department of Health and Family Welfare (Tamil Nadu)|Department of Health and Family Welfare]] has confirmed a total of 1,821 cases, including 23 deaths and 960 recoveries, as of 25 April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nhmtn.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/095ad0a1c0254b058fa36b32d1ab1977|title=ArcGIS Dashboards|website=nhmtn.maps.arcgis.com|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> As of 20 April 2020, 1302 out of 1,520 ({{Percentage|1302|1520}}) cases were from one cluster linked to a [[Tablighi Jamaat]] religious congregation [[2020 Tablighi Jamaat coronavirus hotspot in Delhi|event]] that took place in [[Delhi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hpq8kc7mWg0|title=Polimer News - \u0b9f\u0bc6\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0bb2\u0bbf \u0bb0\u0bbf\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0ba9\u0bcd\u0bb8\u0bcd, \u0ba4\u0bca\u0b9f\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1\u0b9f\u0bc8\u0baf 1,302 \u0baa\u0bc7\u0bb0\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1 \u0b95\u0bca\u0bb0\u0bcb\u0ba9\u0bbe..!|date=2020-04-20|website=Polimer News - YouTube|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tamil Nadu#Cases by districts|36]] of the [[List of districts of Tamil Nadu|38 districts]] are affected, with [[Chennai district|Chennai]] and [[Coimbatore district|Coimbatore]] being the worst-hit districts. As of 15 April, the state has the most number of coronavirus hotspots in India with 22 districts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/major-metros-in-hotspots-list-tamil-nadu-tops-with-most-11586979604010.html|title=Major metros in hotspots list, Tamil Nadu tops with most|date=2020-04-16|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> However, the mortality rate of {{Percentage|23|1821|2}} is among the lowest in the country. As of 20 April, the infection rate has dropped from 13% on 1 April to 3.6%. As per the Health Department, 80% of the patients are asymptomatic while most deaths are among the elderly and those with co-morbidities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theprint.in/health/tamil-nadu-is-containing-covid-19-well-and-it-is-not-following-bhilwara-model/403663/|title=Tamil Nadu is containing Covid-19 well, and it is not following Bhilwara model|last=Ch|first=Himani|last2=na|date=2020-04-17|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nThe state is under a [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|lockdown]] since 25 March. The [[Government of Tamil Nadu|state government]] has responded to the outbreak by following a contact-tracing, testing and surveillance model.<ref name=\"containmentNews18\">{{cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/tamil-nadu-prepares-for-stage-two-of-coronavirus-outbreak-with-more-home-quarantines-surveillance-2555261.html|title=Tamil Nadu Prepares for Stage Two of Coronavirus Outbreak With More Home Quarantines, Surveillance|website=News18|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329134259/https://www.news18.com/news/india/tamil-nadu-prepares-for-stage-two-of-coronavirus-outbreak-with-more-home-quarantines-surveillance-2555261.html|archive-date=29 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> After facing critisism for low number of tests in early March, the state had increased the total number of tests  by almost seven times between 1\u201319 April.\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{See also|Timeline of the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India/Tamil Nadu medical cases chart}}\n\n{{Sidebar timeline\n| title = Major events in COVID19 pandemic in Tamil Nadu\n\n| years1 = '''07 March'''\n| color1 = tomato\n| events1 = First confirmed case\n\n| years2 = '''15 March'''\n| color2 = brown\n| events2 = Closure of commercial establishments, schools and colleges\n\n| years3 = '''20 March'''\n| color3 = brown\n| events3 = State borders closed\n\n| years4 = '''22 March'''\n| color4 = brown\n| events4 = Janta Curfew - Nation wide\n\n| years5 = '''24 March'''\n| color5 = brown\n| events5 = Section 144 imposed\n\n| years6 = '''25 March'''\n| color6 = black\n| events6 = First reported death <br> Nationwide lockdown imposed till 14 April\n\n| years7 = '''31 March'''\n| color7 = tomato\n| events7 = 100 confirmed cases <br> First case identified from Tablighi Jamaat cluster\n\n| years8 = '''11 April'''\n| color8 = black\n| events8 = 10 reported deaths\n\n| years9 = '''12 April'''\n| color9 = tomato\n| events9 = 1000 confirmed cases\n\n| years10 = '''14 April'''\n| color10 = brown\n| events10 = Nationwide lockdown extended till 3 May\n\n| years11 = '''15 April'''\n| color11 = blue\n| events11 = 100 reported recoveries\n\n| below =\n}}\n\n[[File:Corona Lockdown Tirupur, Tamil Nadu (2).jpg|thumb|Empty store shelves in [[Tiruppur]] due to panic buying prior to lockdown]]\n\n=== March ===\nThe first case of coronavirus was confirmed on 7 March in a resident from [[Kanchipuram]] in [[Chennai]]. He had returned from [[Oman]] and started developing symptoms including fever and cough.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadu-reports-first-case-of-coronavirus-patient-quarantined-in-government-hospital-in-chennai/articleshow/74529929.cms?from=mdr|title=Tamil Nadu reports first case of Coronavirus; patient quarantined in Chennai Government Hospital|date=2020-03-09|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> He was isolated in [[Government General Hospital, Chennai|Rajiv Gandhi Government General Hospital]]. Later, on 10 March, he recovered and tested negative.<ref name=\"TNrecovered\">{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-no-fresh-covid-19-cases-in-tamil-nadu-812479.html?utm_campaign=fullarticle&utm_medium=referral&utm_source=inshorts|title=Coronavirus: No fresh COVID-19 cases in Tamil Nadu|date=10 March 2020|website=Deccan Herald|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter more than a week without new cases, on 18 March, the second person who had travelled by train from Delhi to Chennai confirmed positive. He did not have any history of foreign travel and was described as a domestic case by the state health minister [[C. Vijayabaskar]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Tamil Nadu's 2nd Coronavirus patient raises community transmission fears|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadus-2nd-coronavirus-patient-raises-community-transmission-fears/articleshow/74702335.cms|newspaper=Economic Times|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319193205/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadus-2nd-coronavirus-patient-raises-community-transmission-fears/articleshow/74702335.cms|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, a 21-year-old student who returned from [[Ireland]] tested positive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/health/coronavirus-live-updates-total-covid-19-cases-in-india-death-toll-latest-news-global-market-crash-recession-120031900563_1.html|title=Coronavirus LIVE: India's death toll rises to four|website=Business Standard|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319161417/https://www.business-standard.com/article/health/coronavirus-live-updates-total-covid-19-cases-in-india-death-toll-latest-news-global-market-crash-recession-120031900563_1.html|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, a further three were confirmed positive - A Chennai man who had travelled from [[New Zealand]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/three-more-covid-19-cases-in-state-one-with-no-travel-history/article31146918.ece|title=Three more COVID-19 cases in State, one with no travel history|date=2020-03-24|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-30|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324184127/https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/three-more-covid-19-cases-in-state-one-with-no-travel-history/article31146918.ece|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and two [[Thailand]] nationals in [[Erode]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-reports-17-fresh-coronavirus-cases-tally-now-67-819262.html|title=Tamil Nadu reports 17 fresh coronavirus cases; tally now 67|date=2020-03-30|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> They were admitted to IRT Hospital in Perundurai in Erode. More than 300 people who had come in contact with the three patients were quarantined.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-reports-7th-positive-coronavirus-case-816543.html|title=Tamil Nadu reports 7th positive coronavirus case|date=2020-03-22|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, the first virus-related death in the state was reported after a 54-year-old man in [[Madurai]] died.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.patrikai.com/first-corona-death-in-tn-madurai-men-of-54-years-old-expired/|title=\u0bae\u0ba4\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bae\u0bbf\u0bb4\u0b95\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0bae\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bca\u0bb0\u0bcb\u0ba9\u0bbe \u0baa\u0bb2\u0bbf : 54 \u0bb5\u0baf\u0ba4\u0bc1 \u0ba8\u0baa\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0bae\u0bb0\u0ba3\u0bae\u0bcd {{!}} Patrikai - Tamil Daily - latest online local breaking news & reviews - Tamilnadu, India & World - politics, cinema, cricket, video & cartoon|date=2020-03-25|website=Tamil News patrikai {{!}} Tamil news online {{!}} latest tamil news|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328044912/https://www.patrikai.com/first-corona-death-in-tn-madurai-men-of-54-years-old-expired/|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Five others were infected - four Indonesians and their travel guide from Chennai.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadu-reports-five-new-coronavirus-cases-tally-goes-up-to-23/articleshow/74810591.cms|title=Tamil Nadu reports five new coronavirus cases; tally goes up to 23|author=|newspaper=Economic Times|date = 26 March 2020}}</ref> The five were in quarantine since 22 March in Salem Medical College.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-reports-5-new-cases-covid-19-includes-4-indonesian-travellers-and-1-chennai-man-121103|title=TN reports 5 new cases of COVID-19, includes 4 Indonesian travellers and 1 Chennai man|last=|first=|date=25 March 2020|website=The News Minute|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, a 21-year-old youth who had just returned from a trip to [[Dublin]], Ireland was discharged from the hospital.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://wap.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/covid-19-positive-tamil-nadu-man-with-travel-history-to-ireland-recovers-120032800122_1.html|title=Covid-19 positive Tamil Nadu man with travel history to Ireland recovers|author=|date=28 March 2020|newspaper=Business Standard India|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Two new cases - one each in [[Kumbakonam]] and [[Katpadi]] were reported. With this, the total number of confirmed cases had reached 40 in the state.<ref name=\"MB-0328\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcoronatn.in/files/Media_Bulletin_28_03_2020.pdf|url-status=live|title=Media Bulletin 28 March 2020|website=Health & Family Welfare Department Government of Tamil Nadu|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328125841/https://stopcoronatn.in/files/Media_Bulletin_28_03_2020.pdf|archive-date=28 March 2020|access-date=28 March 2020}}\n</ref>\n\nOn 29 March, the state reported eight more cases (four each from Coimbatore and Erode), all of which were linked to the two [[Thailand|Thai]] nationals and their group who had tested positive. The eight included a 10-month-old baby.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/10-month-old-baby-and-7-more-test-positive-for-covid-19-in-tamil-nadu-states-tally-rises-to-50-818967.html|title=10-month-old baby and 7 more test positive for COVID-19 in Tamil Nadu; state's tally rises to 50|date=29 March 2020|work=Deccan Herald|access-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329142751/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/10-month-old-baby-and-7-more-test-positive-for-covid-19-in-tamil-nadu-states-tally-rises-to-50-818967.html|archive-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> The total number of confirmed cases reached 50.<ref name=\"MB-0329\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_29_03_2020_1_Page_English_77_KB.pdf|url-status=live|title=Media Bulletin 29 March 2020|website=Health & Family Welfare Department Government of Tamil Nadu|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070556/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_29_03_2020_1_Page_English_77_KB.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, 17 new cases were reported, highest till date in the state<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> - 10 male patients from [[Erode]], all of whom have travelled to Delhi were in contact with the Thailand tourists, 5 in Chennai and 1 each in [[Karur]] and [[Madurai]].<ref name=\"MB-0330\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media_Bulletin_30_03_2020_5_Pages_English_226_KB-1.pdf|title=Media Bulletin 30 March 2020|website=Health & Family Welfare Department Government of Tamil Nadu|last=|first=|date=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200414131304/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Media_Bulletin_30_03_2020_5_Pages_English_226_KB-1.pdf|archive-date=14 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n[[File:Corona helmet of Chennai cop.jpg|alt=Chennai cop corona helmet|thumb|A police official in Chennai wearing a unique 'Corona' helmet to dissuade commuters from venturing out during the lockdown.]]\nOn 31 March, 57 new cases were reported, all with a history of travel predominately to [[Delhi]], bringing the total to 124.<ref name=\"IT-57cases\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-reports-57-new-covid-19-cases-in-one-day-79-attended-tablighi-jamaat-state-tally-at-124-1661904-2020-03-31|title=Tamil Nadu reports 57 new Covid-19 cases in one day, 79% attended Tablighi Jamaat. State tally at 124|date=|work=India Today|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It was the highest single day rise till date. 50 of these cases were from [[Namakkal district|Namakkal]] (18), [[Tirunelveli district|Tirunelveli]] (22), [[Kanyakumari district|Kanyakumari]] (4) [[Viluppuram|Villupuram]] (3), [[Madurai district|Madurai]] (2) and [[Thoothukudi district|Thoothukudi]] (1), all had travel history to Delhi.<ref name=\"MB-0331\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_31.03.2020_2_Pages_English_118_KB.pdf|title=Media Bulletin 31 March 2020|last=|first=|date=|website=Health & Family Welfare Department Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070737/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_31.03.2020_2_Pages_English_118_KB.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> Officials had discovered that at least 80 out of 124 confirmed cases (79 per cent) in Tamil Nadu were from one cluster as they are direct or indirect contact of the two Thai nationals who had tested positive for on 21 March.<ref name=\"IT-57cases\" /><ref name=\"Hindu-31March\" /> The Thai nationals, identified as patients 5 and 6 were part of a large group from countries including [[Thailand]], [[Indonesia]], [[Malaysia]], etc. who had visited the state for an annual pilgrimage.<ref name=\"Hindu-31March\">{{Cite news|last=M|first=Serena Josephine|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/25-of-67-patients-directly-or-indirectly-linked-to-thai-nationals/article31212197.ece|title=25 of 67 patients directly or indirectly linked to Thai nationals|date=2020-03-30|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-31|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331163219/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/25-of-67-patients-directly-or-indirectly-linked-to-thai-nationals/article31212197.ece|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This group had also attended a 3-day ''[[Tablighi Jamaat]]'' congregation in [[Nizamuddin Markaz Mosque|Nizamuddin Markaz mosque]], [[New Delhi]] in early March.<ref name=\"March31-DH\">{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-25-out-of-67-in-tamil-nadu-have-contact-or-travel-history-with-thai-nationals-819372.html|title=Coronavirus: 25 out of 67 in Tamil Nadu have contact or travel history with Thai nationals|date=2020-03-30|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> It was estimated that more than 1,500 people from the state had participated in this event.<ref name=\"31MarchNews18\">{{cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/coimbatore-erode-stare-at-crisis-as-tamil-nadu-govt-races-to-trace-scores-back-from-nizamuddin-event-2558131.html|title=Coimbatore, Erode Stare at Crisis as Tamil Nadu Govt Races to Trace Scores Back from Nizamuddin Event|website=News18|access-date=2020-03-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401020556/https://www.news18.com/news/india/coimbatore-erode-stare-at-crisis-as-tamil-nadu-govt-races-to-trace-scores-back-from-nizamuddin-event-2558131.html|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Officials also confirmed that the 54-year-old patient who had died the previous week had also participated in the gathering.  Of 1,500 people who were in the gathering, 1,130 had returned to the state. The government had identified and isolated 515 of the 1,130 people.<ref name=\"IT-57cases\" /> It faced difficulty while trying to map the rest. It had urged people who attended the gathering to step forward and get tested.<ref name=\"31MarchNews18\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-reports-50-more-covid-19-cases/articleshow/74917772.cms|title=Tamil Nadu Coronavirus update: Tamil Nadu reports 50 more Covid-19 cases {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Mar 31|first=Pushpa Narayan {{!}} TNN {{!}} Updated|last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01|last3=Ist|first3=23:31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331211819/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-reports-50-more-covid-19-cases/articleshow/74917772.cms|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Following this, the Nizamuddin Markaz emerged as a new virus hotspot.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/how-nizamuddin-markaz-became-a-hotspot-for-covid-19-8-000-people-identified/story-zedKlaDNTPpbDLdMsgExAM.html|title=How Nizamuddin markaz became Covid-19 hotspot; more than 8,000 attendees identified|date=2020-04-02|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402162727/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/how-nizamuddin-markaz-became-a-hotspot-for-covid-19-8-000-people-identified/story-zedKlaDNTPpbDLdMsgExAM.html|archive-date=2 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== April ===\nOn 1 April, the state reported 110 new cases, all attended the Delhi Nizamuddin event. The total became 234.<ref name=\"MB-0401\"/><ref name=\"April1-IT\">{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-new-coronavirus-cases-linked-nizamuddin-event-tabligh-1662243-2020-04-01|title=Tamil Nadu reports 110 new coronavirus cases, all linked to Nizamuddin event|last=Lobo|first=Shalini|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"TNM-TJ\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/110-more-cases-tamil-nadu-wednesday-all-attended-delhi-jamaat-conference-121630|title=110 more cases in Tamil Nadu on Wednesday, all attended Delhi Jamaat conference|last=|first=|date=|website=The News Minute|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402005422/https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/110-more-cases-tamil-nadu-wednesday-all-attended-delhi-jamaat-conference-121630|archive-date=2 April 2020|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref> Health Secretary Beela Rajesh said that 1103  out of 1500 attendees of the event had been traced and isolated. 658 of their samples had been tested of which,190 tested positive.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/covid-19-tamil-nadu-witnesses-steep-rise-in-cases/articleshow/74935016.cms|title=Covid-19: Tamil Nadu witnesses steep rise in cases|date=2020-04-01|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401210601/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/covid-19-tamil-nadu-witnesses-steep-rise-in-cases/articleshow/74935016.cms|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Some of the participants approached officials themselves after government's request.<ref name=\"TNM-TJ\" /> Family members and close contacts were either taken to quarantine facilities or home quarantined.<ref name=\"TOI-TJcontainment\">{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/special-containment-plan-for-tj-group/articleshow/74939483.cms|title=Tamil Nadu: Special containment plan for Tablighi Jamaat group {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Apr 2|first=Pushpa Narayan {{!}} TNN {{!}} Updated|last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02|last3=Ist|first3=08:57}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, 75 new cases were reported, of which 74 of them attended ''Tablighi Jamaat'' in Delhi.<ref name=\"MB-0402\"/>\n\nOn 3 April, 102 new cases were reported, of which 100 were Delhi event participants. Two others were from Chennai, one with [[Comorbidity|co-morbid]] condition and one US-returnee.<ref name=\"MB-0403\"/>\n\nOn 4 April, 74 new cases were reported, of which 69 were Delhi event participants, 4 were contacts of the event participants. One was from Chennai.<ref name=\"MB-0404\"/><ref name=\"TheHinduApr04\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/74-new-cases-take-tamil-nadus-total-to-485/article31259992.ece|title=Coronavirus {{!}} 74 new cases take Tamil Nadu's total to 485|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405032029/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/74-new-cases-take-tamil-nadus-total-to-485/article31259992.ece|archive-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> Two more deaths were reported, a 51 years old male who attended ''Tablighi Jamaat'' at Villupuram and a female at Theni Government hospital.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/two-dead-of-covid-19-in-tamil-nadu/article31258200.ece#|title=Two dead of Covid-19 in Tamil Nadu|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407055948/https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/two-dead-of-covid-19-in-tamil-nadu/article31258200.ece|archive-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April, 86 new cases were reported of which 85 are related to Delhi event directly or indirectly. A 71 year old from Ramanathapuram who died on Thursday was tested positive. A 60 year old also died in the same hospital as previous patient.<ref name=\"Hindu-0405\">{{Cite news|last=Sujatha|first=R.|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/coronavirus-tn-reports-86-more-covid-19-cases-total-spikes-to-571/article31263138.ece|title=Coronavirus {{!}} Tamil Nadu reports 86 new cases, two more patients die|date=2020-04-05|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406035038/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/coronavirus-tn-reports-86-more-covid-19-cases-total-spikes-to-571/article31263138.ece|archive-date=6 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Health department revealed that 1246 contacts of Tablighi Jamaat participants have been traced and isolated so far.<ref name=\"MB-0405\"/>\n\nOn 6 April, 50 new cases were reported bringing the total cases to 621. 48 of them were returnees of Delhi event.<ref name=\"MB-0406\"/> 101 people who attended a COVID-19 victim's burial were home-quarantined in [[Ramanathapuram district|Ramanathapuram]]. They were not aware of his condition as the test result returned positive after only two days his burial.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/06/over-100-quarantined-after-covid-19-victim-buried-without-precautions-in-tamil-nadu-2126260.html|title=Over 100 quarantined after COVID-19 victim buried without precautions in Tamil Nadu|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407123052/https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/06/over-100-quarantined-after-covid-19-victim-buried-without-precautions-in-tamil-nadu-2126260.html|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 April, 69 new cases were reported, of which 63 were related to Delhi event.<ref name=\"MB-0407\"/>\n\nOn 8 April, 48 new cases were reported bringing total to 738. 42 of those are connected to ''Tablighi Jamaat'' in Delhi.<ref name=\"MB-0408\"/> One among the 42 is a Malaysian national. Government had revealed that 1480 attendees of the Delhi event were traced and isolated. 1716 samples from them and their contacts were tested, of which 679 had returned positive.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/09/tamil-nadu-reports-48-new-covid19-cases-tally-climbs-to-738-2127606.html|title=Tamil Nadu reports 48 new COVID19 cases, tally climbs to 738|date=|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April, the state reported 96 new cases which brought the total cases to 834.<ref name=\"MB-0409\"/>\n\nOn 10 April, 77 new cases were reported bringing total to 911. 70 of those are connected to ''Tablighi Jamaat'' in Delhi. 17 cases were clinically recovered, bringing the total recovered to 44.<ref name=\"MB-0410\"/>\n\nOn 11 April, 58 new cases were reported bringing the total to 969 of which, 47 belonged to the Delhi cluster.<ref name=\"MB-0411\"/> One more died in IRT Government Hospital at Perundurai in Erode, taking the death toll to 10. The state government revealed that it will decide on the [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|lockdown]] extension based on Centre's announcement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-awaits-pms-announcement-on-lockdown-extension-reports-58-more-covid-19-cases-and-one-more-death/articleshow/75098435.cms|title=Tamil Nadu awaits PM's announcement on lockdown extension, reports 58 more Covid-19 cases and one more death {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Mariappan|first=Julie|date=|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412040333/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-awaits-pms-announcement-on-lockdown-extension-reports-58-more-covid-19-cases-and-one-more-death/articleshow/75098435.cms|archive-date=12 April 2020|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 April, 106 new cases were reported bringing the total to 1075.<ref name=\"MB-0412\"/> One death was reported, a 45-year-old women died on previous day evening, she was undergoing treatment at a Government Hospital in Chennai.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/13/covid-19-tamil-nadu-scales-1000-mark-93560-people-quarantined-for-28-days-2129281.html|title=COVID-19: Tamil Nadu scales 1000-mark, 93,560 people quarantined for 28 days|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200413023709/https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/13/covid-19-tamil-nadu-scales-1000-mark-93560-people-quarantined-for-28-days-2129281.html|archive-date=13 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The new infections were found in clusters in Chennai - where four were primary sources and Coimbatore - where two primary sources were identified. According to the health department, of the 106 new cases, 90 contracted the infection from them 16 people who had travel history.<ref name=\"Hindu-106cases\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/coronavirus-one-more-death-106-fresh-cases-in-tamil-nadu/article31325855.ece|title=Coronavirus {{!}} One more death, 106 fresh cases in Tamil Nadu|date=2020-04-13|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-13|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200413065713/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/coronavirus-one-more-death-106-fresh-cases-in-tamil-nadu/article31325855.ece|archive-date=13 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 April, 98 new cases were reported bringing the total to 1173.<ref name=\"MB-0413\"/>\n\nOn 14 April, 31 new cases were reported bringing the total to 1204. It was the lowest daily rise since 31 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-reports-lowest-daily-rise-in-covid-19-cases-since-march-31-missing-patient-secured/articleshow/75145246.cms|title=Tamil Nadu reports lowest daily rise in Covid-19 cases since March 31; missing patient secured {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Narayan|first=Pushpa|last2=Marx|first2=Karal|date=|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200415054221/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-reports-lowest-daily-rise-in-covid-19-cases-since-march-31-missing-patient-secured/articleshow/75145246.cms|archive-date=15 April 2020|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> A 96-year-old died, making the total of 12 deaths in the state.<ref name=\"MB-0414\"/>\n\nOn 15 April, 38 new cases were reported in the state of which, 34 were related to Delhi cluster.<ref name=\"MB-0415\"/> Deaths of two men were reported, a 47-year-old man with [[Influenza-like illness|SARI]] in [[Stanley Medical College|Stanley Government hospital]], Chennai and a 59-year-old man in a private hospital, making the total of 14 deaths in the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/15/two-men-die-of-covid-19-in-tamil-nadu-toll-now-14-1242-people-infected-2130568.html|title=Two men die of COVID-19 in Tamil Nadu, toll now 14; 1242 people infected|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 April, 25 new cases were reported bringing total to 1267. One death was reported making total of 15 deaths in the state<ref name=\"MB-0416\"/>\n\nOn 17 April, 56 new cases were reported which brought the total to 1323.<ref name=\"MB-0417\"/>\n\nOn 18 April, 49 new cases were reported which brought the total to 1372. 82 patients were discharged making total recovered cases as 365.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dinamalar.com/news_detail.asp?id=2523452 |title=\u0ba4\u0bae\u0bbf\u0bb4\u0b95\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bca\u0bb0\u0bcb\u0ba9\u0bbe\u0bb5\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1 1372 \u0baa\u0bc7\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0baa\u0bbe\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1; 15 \u0baa\u0bc7\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0baa\u0bb2\u0bbf&#124; Coronavirus cases in Tamil Nadu rise to 1372 |publisher=Dinamalar |date= |accessdate=2020-04-18}}</ref><ref name=\"MB-0418\"/>\nOn 19 April, 105 new cases were reported, third highest daily increase till date. 46 patients were discharged making total recovered cases as 411.<ref name=\"MB-0419\"/>\n\nOn 20 April, 43 new cases reported in Tamil Nadu bringing the total cases in Tamil Nadu to 1,520.<ref name=\"MB-0420\"/> The infection rate in the state had dropped from 13% on 1 April 2020 to 3.6%.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Dubey|first=Jyotindra|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/health/covid-19-delhi-has-highest-infection-rate-tamil-nadu-is-showing-recovery-120042000685_1.html|title=Covid-19: Delhi has highest infection rate, Tamil Nadu is showing recovery|date=2020-04-20|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 April, 33 new cases reported in Tamil Nadu bringing the total cases to 1,629. 27 patients were discharged making total discharged to 662. No death were reported for the day.<ref name=\"MB-0422\"/>\n\nOn 23 April, [[Dharmapuri district]] reported its first COVID-19 case, 54 new cases were reported in the state bringing the total cases to 1,683. 2 more died. 90 patients were discharged making total discharged to 752.<ref name=\"MB-0423\"/>\n\nOn 24 April, 72 new cases were reported, of which 52 cases are from Chennai, Total confirmed cases stood at 1755. 2 more died which took the total fatality to 22. 114 patients were discharged making total discharged to 886.<ref name=\"MB-0424\"/>\n\n== Cases ==\nThe data below are based on Health and Family Welfare Department of Tamil Nadu daily reports.\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India/Tamil Nadu medical cases}}\n\n=== Cases by districts ===\n<div style=\"display: flex; width: 100%;\">\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India/Tamil Nadu medical cases by district}}\n</div>\n\n==== Districts without confirmed cases ====\nThe following districts have not reported any cases and are classified as 'Green' zones.<ref name=\"TOI-zones\">{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-wants-lockdown-extended-by-two-weeks-but-will-await-pm-modis-call/articleshow/75106907.cms|title=Tamil Nadu Lockdown: Tamil Nadu wants lockdown extended by two weeks, but will await PM Modi's call {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Mariappan|first=Julie|date=|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200413154126/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-wants-lockdown-extended-by-two-weeks-but-will-await-pm-modis-call/articleshow/75106907.cms|archive-date=13 April 2020|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n* [[Krishnagiri district|Krishnagiri]]\n* [[Mayiladuthurai district|Mayiladuthurai]]\n\n== Testing ==\nThe government started screening passengers arriving at the airports in January. It had screened 2,10,538 passengers as of 1 April. As of 16 April, More than 1 lakh passengers have been placed under quarantine.<ref name=\"TNIE-0case\" />\n\nBy 16 March, following [[Indian Council of Medical Research|ICMR]]'s guidelines to test for community transmission, the state had tested 22 random samples of people with [[influenza]] and severe acute respiratory infection (SARI) for [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus|coronavirus]]. All tested negative.<ref name=\"scroll-tests\">{{cite web|url=https://scroll.in/pulse/956278/why-kerala-has-done-more-coronavirus-tests-than-tamil-nadu-and-why-this-must-change|title=Why Kerala has done more coronavirus tests than Tamil Nadu \u2013 and why this must change|last=Yamunan|first=Sruthisagar|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328121533/https://scroll.in/pulse/956278/why-kerala-has-done-more-coronavirus-tests-than-tamil-nadu-and-why-this-must-change|archive-date=28 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> By 10 April, of 577 SARI patients tested, five were positive.<ref name=\"SARI-10Apr\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-india-second-icmr-report-random-sampling-test-results-shows-possible-community-transmission-1665290-2020-04-10|title=Coronavirus: Second ICMR report on random sampling test results shows possible community transmission|last=DelhiApril 10|first=Milan Sharma New|last2=April 10|first2=2020UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16|last3=Ist|first3=2020 10:17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412160840/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-india-second-icmr-report-random-sampling-test-results-shows-possible-community-transmission-1665290-2020-04-10|archive-date=12 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Testing rates ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"float:right; clear:right; font-size:90%;\"\n|+Summary of test results\n!Samples tested\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |72,403\n|-\n!Tests per 10,000 people\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |{{formatnum:{{#expr:72403/72147030*10000 round 1}}}}\n|-\n!Tested positive\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |1,755\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:right;\" |{{As of|2020|April|24}}<ref name=\"MB-0424\"/>\n|}\nDuring the first half of March, the state faced criticism for the low number of tests. By 16 March, it had only tested 90 samples while neighbouring Kerala and Karnataka had tested more than 1500 and 750 samples.<ref name=\"Testing-TOI\">{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/in-tamil-nadu-patients-doctors-call-for-increased-tests-on-coronavirus/articleshow/74647117.cms|title=Coronavirus Tamil Nadu Updates: In Tamil Nadu, patients &amp; doctors call for increased tests on coronavirus {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|date=16 March 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321071302/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/in-tamil-nadu-patients-doctors-call-for-increased-tests-on-coronavirus/articleshow/74647117.cms|archive-date=21 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-31|agency=TNN}}</ref> The director of Public Health defended the state's low number of tests by saying that Kerala saw more travel from coronavirus-affected countries which is why it had detected more cases.<ref name=\"scroll-tests\" /> The Public Health department had also said that the state follows test protocols established by the [[Ministry of Health and Family Welfare|Union Health Ministry]].<ref name=\"scroll-tests\" /><ref name=\"Testing-TOI\" /> Following the Delhi Nizamuddin event, the families of all identified participants were tested regardless of whether they showed symptoms or not.<ref name=\"TOI-TJcontainment\" />\n\nTamil Nadu has the highest the percentage of positive samples among total samples tested in the country at 13% as of 7 April. This has been attributed to detection of cases related to the Tablighi Jamaat gathering in Delhi.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiaspend.com/13-of-samples-in-tamil-nadu-are-testing-positive-4-in-india/|title=13% of samples in Tamil Nadu are testing positive, 4% in India {{!}}|last=Raman|first=Shreya|date=2020-04-08|website=www.indiaspend.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200413054301/https://www.indiaspend.com/13-of-samples-in-tamil-nadu-are-testing-positive-4-in-india/|archive-date=13 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 April, the health officials of the state said that they have changed the testing strategy to \u201caggressive testing\u201d, also including asymptomatic individuals.<ref name=\"DNext-12Apr2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dtnext.in/News/TamilNadu/2020/04/12183523/1224770/Tamil-Nadu-crosses-1000mark-in-coronavirus-cases.vpf|title=Tamil Nadu COVID-19 cases cross 1000, eight doctors contract virus|last=100010509524078|date=2020-04-12|website=dtNext.in|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The Health Secretary also said the state is looking to employ the 24,000 real time  [[Reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction|Reverse-Transcription Polymerase Chain Reaction]] (RT-PCR) test kits that it has in possession for more stringent testing. \u201cOur strategy is to ramp up testing using RT-PCR kits. These testing kits are of the gold standard and their results are completely reliable. We will use the RT-PCR test kits to aggressively test primary and secondary contacts.\" the official said.<ref name=\"DH-13Apr2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/coronavirus-with-over-1000-cases-tn-changes-testing-strategy-825043.html|title=Coronavirus: With over 1,000 cases, TN changes testing strategy|date=2020-04-13|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The move was welcomed health professionals. Many politicians and media persons have reiterated WHOs advice of \"test, test and test\".\n\nOn 14 April, the Chennai Corporation revealed that it plans to collect 40,000 swab samples, including 10,000 from containment zones. It has set up 35 walk-in kiosks for the purpose.<ref name=\"TNM-tradecenter\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/trade-centre-chennai-converted-550-bed-covid-19-quarantine-ward-122629 |title=Trade centre in Chennai converted into a 550-bed COVID-19 quarantine ward |website=www.thenewsminute.com|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\nBy 19 April, the state's number of tests per 10,000 people had increased from 0.4 on 1 April to 4.1, which was almost a seven-fold increase.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Rapid test kits ===\nOn 6 April after ICMR's approval, the state government placed an independent order to purchase around one lakh serology-based [[Rapid diagnostic test|rapid test kits]] from China, that can return quick results and are expected to be used for mass testing in smaller towns and rural areas.<ref name=\"HT-response2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/5-lessons-from-tamil-nadu-s-book-how-the-state-is-fighting-covid-19/story-Sl4kD5HZksOIuOTRDm2OeM.html|title=5 lessons from Tamil Nadu's book: How the state is fighting Covid-19|date=2020-04-07|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407165126/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/5-lessons-from-tamil-nadu-s-book-how-the-state-is-fighting-covid-19/story-Sl4kD5HZksOIuOTRDm2OeM.html|archive-date=7 April 2020|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref name=\"DH-13Apr2\"/> They were expected to be delivered by 9 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dtnext.in/News/TamilNadu/2020/04/06155451/1223661/1-lakh-rapid-test-kits-to-speed-up-COVID19-screening-.vpf|title=Tamil Nadu to deploy 1 lakh rapid test kits to speed up COVID-19 screening|last=100010509524078|date=2020-04-06|website=dtNext.in|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407044426/https://www.dtnext.in/News/TamilNadu/2020/04/06155451/1223661/1-lakh-rapid-test-kits-to-speed-up-COVID19-screening-.vpf|archive-date=7 April 2020|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>  On 11 April, the Chief Secretary K Shanmugam said that the consignment meant for India was reportedly diverted to the [[United States]], causing delay.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/rapid-testing-not-arrived-yet-consignment-diverted-us-tamil-nadu-chief-secy-1665964-2020-04-11|title=Rapid testing haven't arrived yet, consignment diverted to US: Tamil Nadu chief secy|last=ChennaiApril 11|first=Akshaya Nath|last2=April 11|first2=2020UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12|last3=Ist|first3=2020 21:09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412071909/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/rapid-testing-not-arrived-yet-consignment-diverted-us-tamil-nadu-chief-secy-1665964-2020-04-11|archive-date=12 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The delay affected the testing rate of the state. The director of public health K Kolandaswamy said \"It is admittedly one of our biggest weakness, but we decided there is no point in waiting for the kits. We have to use every minute in this period resourcefully.\" Instead of waiting, the health department has decided to use the existing RT-PCR kits for mass screening.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/why-tamil-nadu-has-to-do-more-with-less/articleshow/75114082.cms|title=Tamil Nadu Lockdown: Why Tamil Nadu has to do more with less {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|date=|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200414131951/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/why-tamil-nadu-has-to-do-more-with-less/articleshow/75114082.cms|archive-date=14 April 2020|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nAfter several delays, 24,000 rapid test kits reached Chennai on 17 April.<ref name=\"24kRTK\">{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/coronavirus-tamil-nadu-gets-24000-rapid-testing-kits-from-china/articleshow/75194586.cms|title=Tamil Nadu Corona News: Tamil Nadu gets 24,000 rapid testing kits from China {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Narayan|first=Pushpa|date=|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> The state aims to use it for initial testing of close contacts of people who have tested positive and in areas around the containment zones.<ref name=\"HT-rapid\" /> If tested positive, their samples are sent for a confirmatory PCR test.<ref name=\"24kRTK\" /> The state had also ordered an additional 5 lakh rapid test kits and 1 lakh RT-PCR kits.<ref name=\"HT-rapid\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/with-400-000-kits-tn-to-ramp-up-testing/story-GyQ1gZbOr9oVumdeagzK3M.html|title=Coronavirus update: With 400,000 kits, Tamil Nadu to ramp up Covid-19 testing|date=2020-04-11|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412233926/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/with-400-000-kits-tn-to-ramp-up-testing/story-GyQ1gZbOr9oVumdeagzK3M.html|archive-date=12 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"DC-CM17apr\">{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/current-affairs/170420/dip-in-new-cases-makes-tamil-nadu-chief-minister-highly-optimistic.html|title=Dip in new cases makes Tamil Nadu chief minister highly optimistic|last=Venkatesh|first=D. Sekar & M. R.|date=2020-04-17|website=Deccan Chronicle|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\nChief Minister E Palaniswami had urged Prime Minister Narendra Modi to provide COVID-19 rapid test kits and {{INRConvert|1000|c}} immediately to procure medical supplies in a video-conference chaired by Modi and attended by the Chief Ministers of other states on 11 April.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ramakrishnan|first=T.|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/tamil-nadu-chief-minister-urges-prime-minister-modi-to-provide-covid-19-rapid-test-kits-1000-crore-immediately/article31317569.ece|title=Tamil Nadu Chief Minister urges Prime Minister Modi to provide COVID-19 rapid test kits, \u20b91,000 crore immediately|date=2020-04-11|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-12|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412074759/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/tamil-nadu-chief-minister-urges-prime-minister-modi-to-provide-covid-19-rapid-test-kits-1000-crore-immediately/article31317569.ece|archive-date=12 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Testing facilities ===\nInitially, the state only had four government labs for conducting tests for the coronavirus.<ref name=\"scroll-tests\" /> As of 18 April, the state has 31 laboratories (21 government and 10 private) approved by ICMR for testing.<ref name=\"MB-0418\"/> According to reports, private labs has fixed a rate of Rs 4,500 for testing a COVID-19 sample. The state government had announced that it will bear all the expenses.<ref name=\"DNext-12Apr\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dtnext.in/News/TamilNadu/2020/04/12183523/1224770/Tamil-Nadu-crosses-1000mark-in-coronavirus-cases.vpf|title=Tamil Nadu COVID-19 cases cross 1000, eight doctors contract virus|last=100010509524078|date=2020-04-12|website=dtNext.in|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==== Operational testing facilities ====\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===== Public =====\n* [[Coimbatore Medical College]], [[Coimbatore]]\n* [[Government Dharmapuri Medical College]], [[Dharmapuri]]\n* [[Kilpauk Medical College|Government Kilpauk Medical College]], [[Chennai]]\n* [[Mohan Kumaramangalam Medical College|Government Mohan Kumaramangalam Medical College and Hospital]], [[Salem, Tamil Nadu|Salem]]\n* [[Stanley Medical College|Government Stanley Medical College and Hospital]], [[Chennai]] <sup>\u00a7</sup>\n* [[Theni Medical College|Government Theni Medical College]], [[Theni]]\n* [[Thoothukudi Medical College|Government Thoothukudi Medical College]], [[Thoothukudi]]\n* Government Tiruvarur Medical College, [[Thiruvarur|Tiruvarur]]\n* [[Government Vellore Medical College]], [[Vellore]]\n* [[Government Villupuram Medical College|Government Villupuram Medical College and Hospital]], [[Villupuram]]\n* Institute of Vector Control and Zoonoses, [[Krishnagiri]]\n* [[Government Erode Medical College|IRT Perundurai Medical College and Hospital, Perundurai]]\n* [[K.A.P.Viswanatham Government Medical College]], [[Tiruchirapalli]]\n* [[Kanyakumari Government Medical College]], [[Nagercoil]]\n* [[King Institute of Preventive Medicine and Research]] [[Chennai]]\n* [[Madras Medical College]], [[Chennai]]\n* [[Madurai Medical College]], [[Madurai]]\n* [[Pasteur Institute of India]], [[The Nilgiris district|Nilgiris]]\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Government General Hospital, Chennai|Rajiv Gandhi Government General Hospital]], [[Chennai]] ('''[[Viral Research and Diagnostic Laboratories|VRDL]]''')\n* State Public Health Laboratory, Chennai\n* [[Tamil Nadu Government Multi Super Speciality Hospital]], [[Chennai]]\n* [[Thanjavur Medical College]], Thanjavur\n* [[Tirunelveli Medical College]], [[Tirunelveli]]\n\n===== Private =====\n* [[Christian Medical College & Hospital, Vellore|Dept. of Clinical Virology, CMC, Vellore.]]\n* Department of Laboratory Services, Apollo Hospitals Enterprise Ltd, Chennai \n* Neuberg  Ehrlich  Lab  Pvt  Ltd,  46-48  Masilamani  Road,  Balaji Nagar, Chennai \n* [[Sri Ramachandra Institute of Higher Education and Research|Sri Ramachandra Medical College & Research Institute, Porur, Chennai]]\n* Microbiology Lab, Veerakeralam Road, Coimbatore \n* [[YRG Care]], Taramani, Chennai\n* Hitech Diagnostic Centre, Dr.Ganesan's Hitech Diagnostic Centre Pvt Ltd, Poonamallee High Road, Chennai\n* MIOT Hospitals \u2013 Dept of   Lab   Medicine, Manapakkam, Chennai\n* Madras Medical Mission Clinical Lab Services, Mogappair East, Chennai\n* PSG Hospitals Diagnostic Centre, Peelamedu, Coimbatore\n\n<small>'''Sources:''' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://icmr.nic.in/sites/default/files/upload_documents/Govt_Labs_18042020.pdf|title=Govt_Labs_18042020.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://icmr.nic.in/sites/default/files/upload_documents/Private_Labs_18042020.pdf|title=Private_Labs_18042020.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n<br/>'''Note:''' \u00a7 Approved, but not supported by ICMR</small>\n{{col-end}}\n\n=== Test statistics ===\n{{Graph:Chart\n | width = 800\n | type = line\n | xAxisTitle=Date\n | yAxisTitle=Number of samples tested\n | xAxisAngle = -60\n | yAxisMin = 1\n | xType = date\n | xGrid = 1\n | yGrid = 1\n | xAxisFormat = %d %b\n | showSymbols=1\n | legend =\n | x = <!-- March 2020 --> 09 Mar 2020, 10 Mar 2020, 11 Mar 2020, 12 Mar 2020, 13 Mar 2020, 14 Mar 2020, 15 Mar 2020, 16 Mar 2020, 17 Mar 2020, 18 Mar 2020, 19 Mar 2020, 20 Mar 2020, 21 Mar 2020, 22 Mar 2020, 23 Mar 2020, 24 Mar 2020, 25 Mar 2020, 26 Mar 2020, 27 Mar 2020, 28 Mar 2020, 29 Mar 2020, 30 Mar 2020, 31 Mar 2020,\n<!-- April 2020 --> 1 Apr 2020, 2 Apr 2020, 3 Apr 2020, 4 Apr 2020, 5 Apr 2020, 6 Apr 2020, 7 Apr 2020, 8 Apr 2020, 9 Apr 2020, 10 Apr 2020, 11 Apr 2020,12 Apr 2020,13 Apr 2020,14 Apr 2020,15 Apr 2020, 16 Apr 2020, 17 Apr 2020,18 Apr 2020,19 Apr 2020, 20 Apr 2020, 21 Apr 2020, 22 Apr 2020, 23 Apr 2020, 24 Apr 2020, 25 Apr 2020,\n | y1=63,74,75,76,77,79,88,98,140,291,320,333, 412,443,552,743,890,1039,1243,<!--28March data missing-->, 1763,2040,2354,2726,3272,3684, 4248,4612,5015,5305,6095,7267, 8410, 9842,10655, 12746,19255,21994,26005, 29673, 35036, 40876, 46985, 53045,59023,65977,72403,80110,\n | y1Title=Samples tested\n | colors=#2ca02c\n}}\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n | width = 800\n | type =rect\n |showValues=offset:4\n | xAxisTitle=Date\n | yAxisTitle=Number of samples tested per day\n | xAxisAngle = -60\n | yAxisMin = 1\n | xGrid = 1\n | yGrid = 1\n | showSymbols=1\n | legend =\n | x = <!-- March 2020 --> 09 Mar 2020, 10 Mar 2020, 11 Mar 2020, 12 Mar 2020, 13 Mar 2020, 14 Mar 2020, 15 Mar 2020, 16 Mar 2020, 17 Mar 2020, 18 Mar 2020, 19 Mar 2020, 20 Mar 2020, 21 Mar 2020, 22 Mar 2020, 23 Mar 2020, 24 Mar 2020, 25 Mar 2020, 26 Mar 2020, 27 Mar 2020, 28 Mar 2020, 29 Mar 2020, 30 Mar 2020, 31 Mar 2020,\n<!-- April 2020 --> 1 Apr 2020, 2 Apr 2020, 3 Apr 2020, 4 Apr 2020, 5 Apr 2020, 6 Apr 2020, 7 Apr 2020, 8 Apr 2020, 9 Apr 2020, 10 Apr 2020, 11 Apr 2020,12 Apr 2020,13 Apr 2020,14 Apr 2020,15 Apr 2020, 16 Apr 2020, 17 Apr 2020,18 Apr 2020,19 Apr 2020, 20 Apr 2020, 21 Apr 2020, 22 Apr 2020, 23 Apr 2020, 24 Apr 2020, 25 Apr 2020,\n | y1= 63,11,1,1,1,2,9,10,42,151,29,13,79,31,109,191,147,149,204,<!-- 28 March 2020 data missing -->,520,277,314,372,546,412,564,364,403,290,790,1172,1143,1432,813,2091,6509,2739,4011,3668,5363,5840,6109,6060,5978,6954,6426,7707\n | y1Title=New tests per day\n | colors=#2ca02c\n}}\n<small>'''Source:''' Daily bulletins from Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu</small>\n==== Number of samples tested per week ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\"\n|-\n!style=\"width: 12em;\"|Week\n!style=\"width: 10em;\"|New\n!style=\"width: 10em;\"|Total\n!style=\"width: 2em;\"|Sources(s)\n|-\n!Till 8 March\n|63\n|63\n|<ref name=\"MB-0309\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/MediaBulletin090320COVID19.pdf|title=Media Bulletin 09 March 2020|last=|first=|date=|website=Health & Family Welfare Department Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070803/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/MediaBulletin090320COVID19.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!9\u201315 March\n|35\n|98\n|<ref name=\"MB-0316\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/MediaBulletin160320COVID19.pdf|title=Media Bulletin 16 March 2020|last=|first=|date=|website=Health & Family Welfare Department Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070825/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/MediaBulletin160320COVID19.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!16\u201322 March\n|454\n|552\n|<ref name=\"MB-0323\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_23_03_20_%20COVID_19.pdf|title=Media Bulletin 23 March 2020|last=|first=|date=|website=Health & Family Welfare Department Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401070850/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_23_03_20_%20COVID_19.pdf|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!23\u201329 March\n|1488\n|2040\n|<ref name=\"MB-0330\"/>\n|-\n!30 March\u20135 April\n|2975\n|5015\n|<ref name=\"MB-0406\"/>\n|-\n!6\u201312 April\n|7731\n|12746\n|<ref name=\"MB-0413\"/>\n|-\n!13\u201319 April<!--There is slight mismatch b/w weeks and samples before this row, let it be for now. We'll reconcile it once table rows for 2 more weeks-->\n|28130\n|40876\n|<ref name=\"MB-0419\"/>\n|-| colspan=\"4\" |{{Small|Numbers are deduced from daily reports provided by Health and Family Welfare Department.}}\n|}\n\n== Treatment ==\n[[File:CTC Covid-19 quarantine ward.jpg|thumb|Quarantine wards set up in Chennai Trade Center, Nungambakkam being disinfected]]\nThe state has 3,371 ventilators and 29,074 beds in isolation wards according to the [[Department of Health and Family Welfare (Tamil Nadu)|Department of Health and Family Welfare]] as of April 2.<ref name=\"TNHFW\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/|title=Health & Family Welfare Department Government of Tamil Nadu Stop Corona Home|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331222637/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/|archive-date=31 March 2020|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> It has ordered an additional 2,571 ventilators.<ref name=\"DC-CM17apr\"/> The number of hospital beds available is 1.1 per 1000 population and 7.8 per 1000 for elderly population according a [[Brookings Institution|Brookings]] reports.<ref name=\"Brookings\">{{cite web|url=https://www.brookings.edu/blog/up-front/2020/03/24/is-indias-health-infrastructure-equipped-to-handle-an-epidemic/|title=COVID-19 {{!}} Is India's health infrastructure equipped to handle an epidemic?|last=Chakraborty|first=Prachi Singh, Shamika Ravi, and Sikim|date=2020-03-24|website=Brookings|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200409070819/https://www.brookings.edu/blog/up-front/2020/03/24/is-indias-health-infrastructure-equipped-to-handle-an-epidemic/|archive-date=9 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> As of 2 April, 21 government facilities are designated for treating COVID-19 illness cost free. As of 3 April, 25 private colleges and 110 private hospitals in the state are designated for treating COVID-19 illness.<ref name=\"private hosp apr3\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Private-Hospital-List.pdf|title=Private-Hospital-List.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407063519/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Private-Hospital-List.pdf|archive-date=7 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"public Hospitals apr2\">{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Government-Hopital-treating-COVID-19.pdf|title=Government-Hopital-treating-COVID-19.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407063630/https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Government-Hopital-treating-COVID-19.pdf|archive-date=7 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Chennai Trade Centre|Chennai Trade Center]] in [[Nungambakkam]] was converted into a 550-bed COVID-19 quarantine ward on April 14.<ref name=\"TNM-tradecenter\" /> The [[Greater Chennai Corporation]] Commissioner G Prakash said that more such facilities in the city were planned.<ref name=\"TNM-tradecenter\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/2020/apr/14/more-isolation-wards-get-ready-2129795.html|title=More isolation wards get ready|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n== Government response ==\nThe [[Government of Tamil Nadu|state government]] was among the first to launch measures against COVID-19.<ref name=\"TNborder\" /> On 30 January, it had put 78 people who arrived from [[China]] under quarantine.<ref name=\"TNborder\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/coronavirus-outbreak-tamil-nadu-closes-borders-constitutes-task-force-120032201274_1.html|title=Coronavirus outbreak: Tamil Nadu closes borders, constitutes task force|work=Business Standard India|access-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323121451/https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/coronavirus-outbreak-tamil-nadu-closes-borders-constitutes-task-force-120032201274_1.html|archive-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> The state government had announced a {{INRConvert|3280|c|year=2020}} relief package on 24 March. It included financial support of {{INRConvert|1000|year=2020}} to all ration card holders, free rice and other essential commodities in the wake of [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|lockdown]]. It also provided registered [[Hawker (trade)|street vendors]], autorickshaw drivers, migrant labourers and construction workers in the state with similar provisions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/tn-announces-3280-crore-relief-package/article31156022.ece|title=TN announces \u20b93,280-crore relief package|last=Bureau|first=Our|website=@businessline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325143624/https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/tn-announces-3280-crore-relief-package/article31156022.ece|archive-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It had also announced extension periods of three months to make loan and tax payments for all citizens, and one month to pay house rent for workers including migrants across the state.<ref name=\"RentsTNM\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-govt-announces-one-month-rent-freeze-action-can-be-taken-if-house-owners-disobey-121552|title=TN govt announces one month rent freeze for workers, including migrants|last=|first=|date=|website=The News Minute|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Loans-BS\">{{Cite news|last=Narasimhan|first=T. E.|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/covid-19-tamil-nadu-gives-3-month-extension-for-payment-of-taxes-loans-120033101318_1.html|title=Covid-19: Tamil Nadu gives 3-month extension for payment of taxes, loans|date=31 March 2020|work=Business Standard India|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Currently, the government operates 311 relief camps and shelters for migrant workers.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/coronavirus-centre-files-report-on-migrant-workers/article31283896.ece|title=Centre files report on migrant workers|date=2020-04-07|work=The Hindu|access-date=|url-status=live|language=en-IN|issn=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408015424/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/coronavirus-centre-files-report-on-migrant-workers/article31283896.ece|archive-date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MB-0401\" />\n\nEarlier, it had allocated sum of {{INRConvert|60|c}} from disaster relief fund to deal with the crisis. It had also taken steps to provide medicines for the next two months to patients with hypertension, diabetes mellitus, HIV and TB while also monitoring pregnant women who are due within that time.<ref name=\"Hindu-CM\">{{Cite news|last=Palaniswami|first=Edappadi K.|url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/lead/an-eye-each-on-containment-and-welfare/article31221845.ece|title=Tamil Nadu CM writes on how the State is stopping the pandemic in its tracks|date=2020-04-01|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401124254/https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/lead/an-eye-each-on-containment-and-welfare/article31221845.ece|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/pregnant-women-to-be-monitored/article31167753.ece|title=Pregnant women to be monitored|date=2020-03-25|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-02|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326171940/https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/pregnant-women-to-be-monitored/article31167753.ece|archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March in the wake of the nationwide lockdown, the government announced a one-month rent freeze for students and workers, including migrant labourers.<ref name=\"RentsTNM\" /> It also extended the time to make payments including loans and taxes by three months.<ref name=\"Loans-BS\" />\n[[File:Covid-19 in India- Market in TN\u2019s Tiruppur sets up disinfection tunnel for customers.webm|thumb|Disinfection tunnel set up in a market in [[Tiruppur district|Tiruppur]] before ban on its usage.]]\nOn 2 April, the government announced care package of {{INRConvert|1000|year=2020}} and monthly allowed ration of food supply for each household.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stopcoronatn.in/files/8496PDIPR-P.R.No.249-TNPDS-PressRelease-Date02.04.2020.pdf|title=TNPDS-PressRelease-Date02.04.2020|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe government has established helplines for public.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/whomtocontact.html|title=Health & Family Welfare Department Government of Tamil Nadu Stop Corona Contact Information|website=stopcorona.tn.gov.in|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> It also released an app for officials to monitor people under home quarantine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-tn-tracks-movements-of-home-quarantine-people-through-a-mobile-app-817853.html|title=Coronavirus: TN tracks movements of home quarantine people through a mobile app|date=2020-03-26|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 April, Coimbatore district administration made usage of face masks compulsory for all.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Coimbatore/mask-made-compulsory-in-coimbatore/article31333781.ece|title=Mask made compulsory in Coimbatore|date=2020-04-13|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-14|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\n=== Suspensions and closedowns ===\nOn 15 March, Chief minister [[Edappadi K. Palaniswami|Edappadi K Palaniswami]] ordered closure of primary schools throughout the state while shutting theatres, commercial complexes and malls.<ref name=\"indiatoday1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-govt-to-release-rs-60-crore-disaster-relief-funds-to-tackle-coronavirus-shuts-primary-schools-1655752-2020-03-15|title=Tamil Nadu govt to release Rs 60 crore disaster relief fund to tackle coronavirus, shuts primary schools|last=Lobo|first=Shalini|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316010520/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-govt-to-release-rs-60-crore-disaster-relief-funds-to-tackle-coronavirus-shuts-primary-schools-1655752-2020-03-15|archive-date=16 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Hindu-CM\" /> He had also ordered to close state borders with [[Karnataka]], [[Kerala]] and [[Andhra Pradesh]] on March 20 until March 31 and constituted a task force to closely monitor the preventive measures against the viral outbreak.<ref name=\"TNborder\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/tn-closes-border-roads-movement-of-essentials-allowed/1774787|title=TN closes border roads, movement of essentials allowed|last=|first=|date=|website=Outlook India|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323121451/https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/tn-closes-border-roads-movement-of-essentials-allowed/1774787|archive-date=23 March 2020|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, the state government extended '[[Janata Curfew|''Janata curfew'']]' to Monday morning 5 am.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadu-govt-extends-janata-curfew-till-monday-morning/articleshow/74758800.cms|title=Tamil Nadu govt extends 'Janata curfew' till Monday morning|date=2020-03-22|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> The next day, it announced that prohibitory orders under [[Unlawful assembly|Section 144]] will start from 24 March 6 pm until March 31 which prohibits gatherings of more than 5 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-imposes-section-144-week-no-gatherings-more-5-people-120912|title=TN imposes Section 144 for a week, no gatherings of more than 5 people|last=|first=|date=23 March 2020|website=www.thenewsminute.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323102039/https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-imposes-section-144-week-no-gatherings-more-5-people-120912|archive-date=23 March 2020|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Narendra Modi]] announced a [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|nationwide lockdown]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/23/asia/coronavirus-covid-19-update-india-intl-hnk/index.html|title=India places millions under lockdown to fight coronavirus|author1=Helen Regan|author2=Esha Mitra|author3=Swati Gupta|date=|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325053856/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/23/asia/coronavirus-covid-19-update-india-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=25 March 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April, the state's chief secretary K Shanmugam said that it favoured a two-week extension of the lockdown, but would wait for PM's announcement. When questioned about other states extending the lockdown, Shanmugam said that \u201cIt is not a decision to be taken by a single state. Ours will be in tune with the PM\u2019s announcement\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-wants-lockdown-extended-by-two-weeks-but-will-await-pm-modis-call/articleshow/75106907.cms|title=Tamil Nadu Lockdown: Tamil Nadu wants lockdown extended by two weeks, but will await PM Modi's call {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Mariappan|first=Julie|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200413154126/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-wants-lockdown-extended-by-two-weeks-but-will-await-pm-modis-call/articleshow/75106907.cms|archive-date=13 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 April, the state government extended the lock-down till 30 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/coronavirus-lockdown-tamil-nadu-extends-restrictions-till-april-30-day-before-pm-modis-address-to-nation/1927168/|title=Coronavirus lockdown: Tamil Nadu extends restrictions till April 30 day before PM Modi's address to nation|date=2020-04-13|website=The Financial Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 April, the state government extended the lockdown till May 3 without any further relaxation.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jesudasan|first=Dennis S.|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/tamil-nadu-decides-to-continue-lockdown-till-may-3/article31387640.ece|title=Tamil Nadu decides to continue lockdown till May 3|date=2020-04-20|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-21|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 April, the government issued an order to relax the lockdown in non-containment zones. This included [[National Rural Employment Guarantee Act, 2005|MGNREGA]] works, construction in rural areas and continuous process industries including refineries, steel, glass and cement plants.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tn-govt-relaxes-curbs-allows-job-scheme-construction-in-villages/articleshow/75335170.cms|title=Tamil Nadu government relaxes curbs, allows job scheme, construction in villages {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Apr 24|first=Julie Mariappan {{!}} TNN {{!}} Updated|last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24|last3=Ist|first3=06:20}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 April, the Chief Minister announced that a complete lockdown would be imposed in Chennai, Coimbatore, Madurai, Salem and Tiruppur [[Municipal corporation|corporations]]. The lockdown will be in effect from 6 a.m. on 26 April to 9 p.m. on 29 April in Chennai, Coimbatore and Madurai. Meanwhile, in Salem and Tiruppur, it will be imposed from 6 a.m. on 26 April to 9 p.m. on 28 April. The statement said that except certain essential services, no shops will be allowed to open.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jesudasan|first=Dennis S.|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/complete-lockdown-for-four-days-in-chennai-madurai-and-coimbatore-tamil-nadu-chief-minister-says/article31423203.ece|title=Complete lockdown for four days in Chennai, Madurai and Coimbatore, says Tamil Nadu Chief Minister|date=2020-04-24|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-24|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\n=== Containment measures ===\nStickers announcing that \"COVID-19/Do not Visit/Home under quarantine,\" were pasted on the doors of houses of foreign returnees to warn the public.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/mar/27/54000-people-who-landed-from-overseas-to-be-home-quarantined-2122007.html|title=54,000 people who landed from overseas to be home quarantined|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401214313/https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/mar/27/54000-people-who-landed-from-overseas-to-be-home-quarantined-2122007.html|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref> Authorities had also marked their arms with home quarantine stamps.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/mar/24/tamil-nadu-goes-under-lockdown-home-quarantine-stickers-pasted-on-doors-of-foreign-returnees-2121106.html|title=Tamil Nadu goes under lockdown; home quarantine stickers pasted on doors of foreign returnees|website=The New Indian Express|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326175649/https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/mar/24/tamil-nadu-goes-under-lockdown-home-quarantine-stickers-pasted-on-doors-of-foreign-returnees-2121106.html|archive-date=26 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Government launched a mobile application to allow people under home quarantine to interact healthcare professionals for getting medical advice and counselling.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-tamil-nadu-launches-app-to-provide-advice-to-those-under-home-quarantine-816562.html|title=Coronavirus: Tamil Nadu launches app to provide advice to those under home quarantine|date=2020-03-22|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = vertical\n | width = 200\n | image1 = COVID19 Containment measure in Kanchipuram, Tamil Nadu - 1.png\n | caption1 = A street is closed-off by municipality in Kanchipuram as a containment measure.\n | image2 = COVID19 Containment measure in Kanchipuram, Tamil Nadu.png\n | caption2 = Same street from inside the containment.\n}}\n\nOn 28 March, government announced plans for creating containment zones to stop the community spread. The containment zones of 5&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> radius around the residences of infected across 16 districts were set up. It is ringed by an additional 3&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> buffer zone.<ref name=\"2Apr-DH\">{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-screens-households-in-vulnerable-areas-to-prevent-coronavirus-spread-819999.html|title=Tamil Nadu screens households in vulnerable areas to prevent coronavirus spread|date=2020-04-01|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref name=\"containmentDH\">{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-coronavirus-cases-rises-to-74-nizamuddin-link-to-a-chunk-of-it-surfaces-819633.html|title=Tamil Nadu coronavirus cases rises to 74, Nizamuddin link to a chunk of it surfaces|date=2020-03-31|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\"31MarchNews18\" /> Active surveillance inside these zones along with passive surveillance outside of it to trace the contacts of the infected has been initiated. People found infected are quarantined and the area where they lived is added into the containment plan.<ref name=\"2Apr-DH\" /><ref name=\"CM-News18\">{{cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/politics/over-2-lakh-passengers-screened-43000-in-home-quarantine-tamil-nadu-cm-assures-state-ready-to-battle-covid-19-2559869.html|title='Over 2 Lakh Passengers Screened, 43,000 in Home Quarantine': Tamil Nadu CM Assures State Ready to Battle Covid-19|date=2020-04-01|website=News18|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Houses inside the containment zones are surveyed and disinfected every day.<ref name=\"HT-response2\"/>\n\nFrom 29 March, as part of its containment plan, the government had screened 3,96,147 people in their houses inside containment zones of 16 affected districts for fever and other symptoms. It was carried out by over 2,000 personnel.<ref name=\"containmentDH\" /><ref name=\"CM-News18\" /> It was in process of screening up to 7 lakh persons.<ref name=\"2Apr-DH\" />\n\nAs of 31 March, 74,533 passengers who had returned from affected countries are being monitored under 28 day home quarantine. 3470 have completed this quarantine. 79 are currently in institutional quarantine facilities across the state.<ref name=\"MB-0330\"/>\n\nOn 11 April, the state deployed 12 'Special Task Teams' each comprising a [[Indian Administrative Service|IAS]]/[[Indian Police Service|IPS]] officers to coordinate with the respective district collectors to manage the pandemic-affected districts. The teams monitor contact tracing and ensures quick sampling, testing and release of results.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kumar|first=S. Vijay|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/coronavirus-tamil-nadu-deploys-senior-bureaucrats-to-manage-pandemic-in-districts/article31317820.ece|title=Coronavirus {{!}} Tamil Nadu deploys senior bureaucrats to manage pandemic in districts|date=2020-04-11|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-11|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411140319/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/coronavirus-tamil-nadu-deploys-senior-bureaucrats-to-manage-pandemic-in-districts/article31317820.ece|archive-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe state has categorised affected districts into three zones based on the number of cases. Districts with less than ten cases fall under yellow zone, while the ones with 10\u201325 cases are classified as orange zones. Districts with more than 25 cases are classified as red zones.<ref name=\"TOI-zones\" />\n\n=== Medical supplies ===\nThe newly built [[Tamil Nadu Government Multi Super Speciality Hospital|Omandurar Government Multispeciality Hospital]] in Chennai was converted with 500 beds to exclusively treat COVID-19 patients.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kannan|first=Ramya|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu-announces-dedicated-hospital-for-covid-19-patients/article31146741.ece|title=Tamil Nadu announces dedicated hospital for COVID-19 patients|date=2020-03-24|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-24|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328230331/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu-announces-dedicated-hospital-for-covid-19-patients/article31146741.ece|archive-date=28 March 2020|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref name=\"Hindu-CM\" /> The government had also issued appointment order to recruit 530 doctors, 1,000 nurses and 1,508 lab technicians with immediate effect due to the situation. Orders for 200 new ambulances in the state have also been placed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://zeenews.india.com/india/tamil-nadu-recruits-530-doctors-1508-lab-technicians-1000-nurses-to-contain-coronavirus-covid-19-outbreak-cm-k-palaniswami-2272083.html|title=Tamil Nadu recruits 530 doctors, 1508 lab technicians, 1000 nurses to contain coronavirus COVID-19 outbreak: CM K Palaniswami|date=2020-03-27|website=Zee News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327100522/https://zeenews.india.com/india/tamil-nadu-recruits-530-doctors-1508-lab-technicians-1000-nurses-to-contain-coronavirus-covid-19-outbreak-cm-k-palaniswami-2272083.html|archive-date=27 March 2020|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref name=\"CM-News18\" />\n\nOn 3 April, in order to ease the strain on the state's healthcare system, the government announced an incentive package of 30% capital investment with a cap of {{INRConvert|20|c}} for new manufacturers of medical equipment such as [[ventilator]]s, [[Personal protective equipment|PPE kits]], [[N95 mask|N-95 masks]], multi para monitors and drugs such as [[hydroxychloroquine]], [[azithromycin]] and [[Vitamin C|vitamin C tablets]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.investindia.gov.in/team-india-blogs/tamil-nadu-fights-covid-19-business-way|title=Tamil Nadu fights COVID-19 the business way|website=www.investindia.gov.in|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref name=\"HT-response2\"/> After the announcement, eight small and medium-scale companies approached the government to manufacture the required medical equipment. [[Tamil Nadu Medical Services|Tamil Nadu Medical Services Corporation]] said that it would purchase at least 50% of the equipment manufactured by these companies between May and June.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/8-firms-offer-to-supply-ppe-kits-to-tamil-nadu/articleshow/75089933.cms|title=8 firms offer to supply PPE kits to Tamil Nadu {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|date=|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412123252/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/8-firms-offer-to-supply-ppe-kits-to-tamil-nadu/articleshow/75089933.cms|archive-date=12 April 2020|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Legal action ===\nAs of 16 April, 1,94,995 cases have been registered, 2,08,139 persons have been arrested, and 1,79,827 vehicles have been seized in the state for defying lockdown.<ref name=\"TNIE-0case\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/17/is-tamil-nadu-nearing-0-cases-scenario-2131220.html|title=Is Tamil Nadu nearing 0-cases scenario?|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n== Impact ==\n{{see also|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n=== Economy ===\nOn 23 April, the state government exempted e-commerce companies of food processing units, export/import packing houses, research facilities agriculture and horticulture activities from lockdown restrictions. It also exempted bed-side attendants and caregivers of senior citizens.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==== Agriculture ====\nThe nationwide lockdown has impacted farmers and floriculturists in the state. The Tamil Nadu Federation of All Farmers' Association said that about 15 lakh acres of summer paddy and 8 lakh acres of groundnuts across the state were affected due absence of labour for harvesting amid lockdown. Perishables such as fruits and vegetables cannot be taken to markets without transportation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.in/india/news/almost-15-lakh-acres-of-land-in-tamil-nadu-stands-bare-as-lockdown-grounds-farmers/articleshow/74830495.cms|title=Almost 15 lakh acres of land in Tamil Nadu stands bare as lockdown grounds farmers|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\n==== Food and grocery supply ====\nShops dealing food takeaways, groceries, fruits and vegetables, dairy, meat and fish were allowed to function during the lockdown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/galleries/nation/2020/mar/24/tamil-nadu-lockdown-from-hospitals-to-food-delivery-what-services-will-be-affected-and-exempted-f-102808.html|title=Tamil Nadu lockdown: From hospitals to food delivery, what services will be affected and exempted. Find out|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> Online food delivery services were briefly banned<ref>{{Cite news|last=Shrivastava|first=Aditi|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/chennai-bans-delivery-of-cooked-food/articleshow/74837380.cms?from=mdr|title=Chennai bans delivery of cooked food|date=2020-03-27|work=The Economic Times|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://entrackr.com/2020/03/swiggy-and-zomato-not-allowed-to-deliver-in-tamil-nadu/|title=Swiggy and Zomato not allowed to deliver in Tamil Nadu|last=Upadhyay|first=Harsh|date=26 March 2020|website=Entrackr|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327081146/https://entrackr.com/2020/03/swiggy-and-zomato-not-allowed-to-deliver-in-tamil-nadu/|archive-date=27 March 2020|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> and allowed later by the government after imposing some regulations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/covid-19-tamil-nadu-allows-swiggy-zomato-other-apps-to-home-deliver-cooked-food/articleshow/74852688.cms|title=Covid-19: Tamil Nadu allows Swiggy, Zomato, other apps to home deliver cooked food {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Sundaram|first=Ram|date=27 March 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329135126/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/covid-19-tamil-nadu-allows-swiggy-zomato-other-apps-to-home-deliver-cooked-food/articleshow/74852688.cms|archive-date=29 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> The government has also issued identification cards for essential service providers that allow supply of goods and services without being stopped by the police.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/essential-service-providers-to-get-id-cards/article31176329.ece|title=Essential service providers to get ID cards|date=2020-03-26|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-18|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> On 4 April, the operating hours of essential stores during lock-down was reduced to 6 am to 1 pm.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/05/tamil-nadu-people-can-buy-essentials-only-between-6-am-to-1-pm-now-2125875.html|title=Tamil Nadu people can buy essentials only between 6 am to 1 pm now|website=The New Indian Express|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406200806/https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/05/tamil-nadu-people-can-buy-essentials-only-between-6-am-to-1-pm-now-2125875.html|archive-date=6 April 2020|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nTo avoid overcrowding and to  in markets, the state has converted bus stations in towns and cities into vegetable markets.<ref name=\"HT-response2\"/> They were also installed with disinfectant tunnels. Later, the government ordered a ban on such tunnels since it was ineffective.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/covid-19-top-health-official-in-tamil-nadu-issues-orders-banning-use-of-disinfection-tunnels-1666070-2020-04-12|title=Covid-19: Top health official in Tamil Nadu issues orders banning use of disinfection tunnels|last=Nath|first=Akshaya|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412060600/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/covid-19-top-health-official-in-tamil-nadu-issues-orders-banning-use-of-disinfection-tunnels-1666070-2020-04-12|archive-date=12 April 2020|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-tamil-nadu-says-no-to-new-disinfection-tunnels-823888.html|title=Coronavirus: Tamil Nadu says no to new disinfection tunnels|date=2020-04-10|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412060557/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-tamil-nadu-says-no-to-new-disinfection-tunnels-823888.html|archive-date=12 April 2020|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> In Chennai, the corporation and horticulture department has started door delivery service of vegetables.<ref name=\"HT-response2\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/08/new-mobile-markets-in-tamil-nadu-to-prevent-people-crowding-vegetable-markets-grocery-stores-2127378.html|title=New 'Mobile Markets' in Tamil Nadu to prevent people crowding vegetable markets, grocery stores|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> [[Amma Unavagam|Amma canteens]] were also functional. They provided free food for sanitation workers during the lockdown period in Chennai.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.thewire.in/article/government/in-lockdown-tamil-nadus-amma-canteens-rise-to-the-occasion|title=In Lockdown, Tamil Nadu's Amma Canteens Rise to the Occasion|website=The Wire|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n=== Education ===\nPrimary schools were closed in the state as early as 15 March.<ref name=\"indiatoday1\"/> On 21 March, the Class 10 SSLC board exams were postponed to beyond April 14, which were due to begin from March 27.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/covid-19-tamil-nadus-class-10-board-exams-postponed/article31127217.ece|title=COVID-19: Tamil Nadu's Class 10 board exams postponed|accessdate=23 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322145203/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/covid-19-tamil-nadus-class-10-board-exams-postponed/article31127217.ece|archive-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> Students of class 1\u20139 in the state will be promoted automatically considering the closure of schools.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/class-1-9-students-will-be-promoted-in-tamil-nadu-due-to-closure-of-schools-cm-11585134717305.html|title=Class 1-9 students will be promoted in Tamil Nadu due to closure of schools: CM|last=|first=|date=25 March 2020|website=Livemint|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325135110/https://www.livemint.com/news/india/class-1-9-students-will-be-promoted-in-tamil-nadu-due-to-closure-of-schools-cm-11585134717305.html|archive-date=25 March 2020|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref> On 16 April, the [[Department of Higher Education (Tamil Nadu)|Department of Higher Education]] postponed the summer semester exams for academic year 2019\u201320 to the beginning of next academic year for all colleges and universities in Tamil Nadu.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Press-Release-Higher-Education-Department-16.04.2020-1-Page-Tamil-26-KB.pdf|title=Press-Release-Higher-Education-Department-16.04.2020-1-Page-Tamil-26-KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Social ===\nOn 10 April in [[Ariyalur district|Ariyalur]], a 60-year-old man in the COVID-19 isolation ward of Ariyalur Government Hospital committed suicide while awaiting his test results. However his results returned negative.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-man-hangs-self-in-isolation-ward-later-tests-negative-for-covid-19-823884.html|title=Tamil Nadu man hangs self in isolation ward; later tests negative for COVID-19|date=2020-04-10|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411052437/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-man-hangs-self-in-isolation-ward-later-tests-negative-for-covid-19-823884.html|archive-date=11 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Reports of thefts from liquor shops, which were shut by the state government, have emerged.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/|title=Business News Today, Stock Market News, Sensex & Finance News|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330035137/https://www.livemint.com/|archive-date=30 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Misinformation and discrimination ==\n{{see also|Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nFalse information regarding the coronavirus started circulating in the social media platform Whatsapp<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/covid-19-tamil-nadu-teachers-use-whatsapp-to-spread-awareness-815828.html|title=COVID-19: Tamil Nadu teachers use WhatsApp to spread awareness|date=2020-03-20|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320222741/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/covid-19-tamil-nadu-teachers-use-whatsapp-to-spread-awareness-815828.html|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> which led to several arrests in the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/03/cops-book-case-against-tamil-nadu-man-for-spreading-rumours-about-coronavirus-on-whatsapp-2125267.html|title=Cops book case against Tamil Nadu man for spreading rumours about coronavirus on WhatsApp|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406122637/https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/apr/03/cops-book-case-against-tamil-nadu-man-for-spreading-rumours-about-coronavirus-on-whatsapp-2125267.html|archive-date=6 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/covid-19-three-tn-youths-arrested-for-spreading-misinformation/articleshow/74675707.cms|title=Covid-19: Three TN youths arrested for spreading misinformation {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|first=Karal|last=Marx|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321075014/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/covid-19-three-tn-youths-arrested-for-spreading-misinformation/articleshow/74675707.cms|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.republicworld.com/india-news/law-and-order/school-teacher-held-for-fake-information-on-covid-19|title=Tamil Nadu school teacher held for fake information on COVID-19|last=World|first=Republic|website=Republic World|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> A 33-year-old [[Quackery|quack]] was detained for deceiving the local people with a vaccine for COVID-19 in Ranipet.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/mar/31/quack-held-for-selling-fake-coronavirus-vaccine-in-tamil-nadu-2124054.html|title=Quack held for selling fake coronavirus vaccine in Tamil Nadu|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406122541/https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/mar/31/quack-held-for-selling-fake-coronavirus-vaccine-in-tamil-nadu-2124054.html|archive-date=6 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The government had warned of legal action against people spreading misinformation on COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/coronavirus-tamil-nadu-warns-of-action-against-people-spreading-false-info-on-covid-19/articleshow/74552383.cms|title=Coronavirus in Tamil Nadu: Tamil Nadu warns of action against people spreading false info on Covid-19 {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Narayan|first=Pushpa|date=|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311022741/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/coronavirus-tamil-nadu-warns-of-action-against-people-spreading-false-info-on-covid-19/articleshow/74552383.cms|archive-date=11 March 2020|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> Twitter removed actor [[Rajinikanth]]'s video citing as misinformation after he claimed a 14-hour stay at home during the Janata Curfew can stop the disease going from \"stage-2\" to \"stage-3\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/regional-cinema/story/twitter-takes-down-rajinikanth-s-janata-curfew-video-for-spreading-misinformation-1658282-2020-03-21|title=Twitter takes down Rajinikanth's Janata Curfew video for spreading misinformation|last=|first=|date=March 21, 2020|website=India Today|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329165753/https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/regional-cinema/story/twitter-takes-down-rajinikanth-s-janata-curfew-video-for-spreading-misinformation-1658282-2020-03-21|archive-date=29 March 2020|access-date=}}</ref> The chief minister [[Edappadi K. Palaniswami|Edappadi Palaniswami]] had asked people not to communalise the coronavirus infection. He also asked people to avoid discrimination saying, \"people should avoid looking at the infected people and families with disgust\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/dont-communalise-coronavirus-infection-tamil-nadu-cm-says/articleshow/74984047.cms|title=Don't communalise coronavirus infection, Tamil Nadu CM says {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Mariappan|first=Julie|date=|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407112036/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/dont-communalise-coronavirus-infection-tamil-nadu-cm-says/articleshow/74984047.cms|archive-date=7 April 2020|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:40%; float:left; text-align:right;\"\n|+Latest statistics\n!Samples Collected\n!style=\" text-align:right\"|80,110{{refn|including 7,145 repeat samples of the same individuals|group=lower-alpha}}\n|-\n|Positive\n|1,821\n|-\n|Negative\n|69,390\n|-\n|Pending\n|1,754\n|-\n!Under quarantine\n!style=\" text-align:right\"|27,302\n|-\n|Government facilities\n|25\n|-\n|Home q